{[%evp 0,2,19,30,14] Chess never stands still, and neither should your preparation. One year after the release of the 2024 edition, it was time for a comprehensive update. Theoretical developments, new high-level games, and deeper refinements have made this repertoire even stronger and more reliable.  What’s New in the 2025 Edition?  - NEW Top-Level Games – Including the 2024 World Championship! When a line gets played in the Ding Liren – Gukesh World Championship Match, you know it’s BIG. That’s right—this repertoire is now backed by World Championship-level preparation.  - Updated Analysis: Every chapter has been meticulously revised to reflect the latest theoretical discoveries, ensuring that your preparation is always one step ahead.  -ALL Video Lessons Re-Recorded Every Chapter video is brand new—clearer, deeper, and better structured than before.   Whether you studied the 2024 edition or are encountering this repertoire for the first time, this update ensures that your preparation is fully optimized for 2025 and beyond.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 (2. d3 {Chapter 1? We’re covering all those little sidelines White tries at move 2.}) (2. c4 d4 {From Chapter 2 to Chapter 4, we’re dealing with 2.c4. My recommendation? 2...d4—strong, aggressive, the best move. I am offering here for Balck only the most principled lines, fully updated for today. You’ll be ready to play for the full point.}) (2. b3 {In Chapters 5 and 6, we will analyze in detail all Reti systems with 2.b3 or 2.e3 Nf6 3.b3. I have extensive experience with these positions from numerous classical, rapid, and blitz games. This is a popular choice for White in faster time controls, and having a clear plan with Black will be a valuable asset.}) 2... Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 (4. d4 {Colle transpositions? We’ve got them covered in Chapter 12. No surprises, no confusion—just clear, effective plans to handle them the right way.}) (4. b3 c5 {Chapters 7 and 8 were already great in 2024, but now they’re even better. I’ve added all the most relevant games from the past year.}) 4... b6 {This is the most important theoretical section, the core of the repertoire.} 5. cxd5 (5. b3 {This is White’s most common continuation, and we’ll cover it in Chapters 9 and 10. My 2024 recommendations were already strong, but I’ve found even more practical and efficient solutions. Less memorization, easier positions, and a clear path to playing for all three results.}) 5... exd5 {This is the most frequently played line by strong Grandmasters against our repertoire today, and we will discuss it in Chapter 11.} 6. g3 $5 {This idea? Big. It’s been played a lot by young GM Vincent Keymer—and guess what? He’s trained by Peter Leko, one of the best theoreticians out there. That means this is serious. We need to know exactly what to do against it, because trust me, more and more players will copy Keymer.} (6. b4 $5 {In 2024, this was a minor move, But everything changed. In just one year, it’s exploded in popularity. Strong Grandmasters everywhere are playing it with White. This is no longer a sideline—it’s real and serious, and we need to be ready. That’s why we’re taking a much deeper look at it now, making sure you’re fully prepared to handle it with confidence.}) *

