{[%evp 0,22,26,16,18,18,12,20,15,13,28,30,29,3,0,-3,33,10,12,-16,16,22,22,29,6]} 1. Nf3 {Welcome to the 15 minutes video!} d5 2. e3 (2. c4 d4 {[%csl Gd4] My recommendation is to go for the ambitious and independent 2...d4. I also believe it is the most principled move for Black.} 3. b4 (3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 e5 {White has two approaches: to play with 0-0 and allow Black to play e4, or to play the classical d3 setup.} 5. O-O $5 {It is an interesting line .White wants to play d3 on the next move, so he has avoided the 5.d3 Bb4+ line.} (5. d3 {I think here it is easier to play for Black, because we don't have to commit all-in, we can get a pleasant position, because the structure is dubious for White in general.} Bb4+ 6. Bd2 $1 {The best.} a5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Na3 {is the main move, with idea Nc2, but I don't like it.} O-O 9. Nc2 Bd6 $15 {You can keep the bishops.}) 5... e4 $1 {Black should play concretely, and it is a matter of who is prepared better here. But after this chapter, it will be you, since we cover everything.} (5... Nf6 {Don't play this move, because after} 6. d3 {White tricked us, since} Bb4 {[%csl Re1,Gg1] doesn't come with check.}) 6. Ne1 h5 $1 {The key move. This is the only justification for the target on e4 that we created.} 7. d3 $1 {The best move for White.} (7. Bxe4 $2 {is a mistake, but of course, we need to know it, since White won a pawn.} Bh3 $17) 7... e3 $1 {The only good move, you need to destroy the pawn structure.} (7... h4 $2 {Don't play this move, because after} 8. dxe4 hxg3 9. fxg3 $1 $14 {White can actually be slightly better here, so you see it is important to know the theory.}) 8. fxe3 {The critical move and now} h4 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gh4g3] Only when the structure is destroyed, so after hxg3 there is no fxg3 option. There are 14 games and only 4 human games. It White follows the engine lines, they can be fine, but over the board it is very difficult to play.}) (3. e3 {White plays in Modern Benoni style.} Nc6 4. exd4 {[%csl Gd4] Now the game will revolve around the control of the d4 square.} (4. b4 {This gambit was first played in Takacs - Rubinstein, 1924, exactly 101 years ago! Despite being objectively dubious, it is still occasionally played today—even by players over 2400.} dxe3 5. fxe3 Nxb4 6. d4 {White's most common continuation.} e5 $1 {Black's key move. If you think this is a typical computer move, you’re completely wrong—Rubinstein already found it in the first recorded game back in 1924!} 7. a3 (7. Nxe5 Bf5 8. Na3 Bd6 $36) 7... Nc6 $1 {the right continuation.} 8. d5 {White's most popular move.} Nb8 $5 {the simplest way in my opinion.} 9. Nxe5 Bd6 10. Nf3 Nf6 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gf8e8] 00-Nbd7-Re8 next. Equal material but positional advantage and easy play for Black.}) 4... Nxd4 5. Nxd4 Qxd4 6. Nc3 c6 {[%csl Yc3,Gc6] very useful move to limit Nc3.} ({we cannot start with the immediate} 6... Nh6 $2 {because of} 7. Nd5 $1 $16) 7. d3 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5] Don't be afraid of Bxh6, as it is simply bad for White. The correct knight development is Nh6 → Nf5.} 8. Be3 (8. Bxh6 $2 {positional mistake.} gxh6 $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh8g8,Gc8f5] We have the bishop pair and excellent piece activity, controlling many key squares. We can continue with Bf5 → Rg8.}) 8... Qd8 {the main move. It's a good one, but not the only one.} 9. d4 Nf5 10. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Gd2e3] Important move, as White should be ready to recapture on e3 with the queen.} (10. Be2 $6 Nxe3 11. fxe3 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8h6,Ge8g8] Bg7 or Bh6 and 00 next}) 10... g6 {White can now decide whether to castle short or long.}) 3... f6 4. e3 {The main move.} e5 5. c5 {is the main move, but here nothing changed.} a5 $1 {The best.} 6. Qa4+ {Black has some options, but in this database my offer is:} Bd7 {My recommendation now, because I realised that it just makes the variation empty for White.} 7. b5 Bxc5 8. Bc4 {The only logical move.} Ne7 9. exd4 {has to be played.} exd4 10. Ba3 $1 {The main line.} (10. O-O $2 {Famous mistake.} Bg4 $1 {And it is not easy to defend f3.} 11. Qb3 a4 12. Qd3 Bf5 13. Qe2 d3 {And the position is better for Black.} 14. Qe1 Qd6 15. Nc3 Qf4 $17) (10. Bb2 $2 {is also a mistake.} Bg4 $1 11. Nxd4 Qd6 $36 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Nd7-Nb6 next with huge initiative.}) 10... Bxa3 $1 {This is the strongest.} 11. Qxa3 {Psychologically harder to play because the knight on b1 is out of the game for now, but objectively stronger.} (11. Nxa3 $2 {It's a mistake.} Bg4 12. Nxd4 Qd6 $15 {And typical moves next.}) 11... c6 $1 {This is the cleanest equalizer.} 12. Nxd4 cxb5 {And trade everything.} 13. Nxb5 Bxb5 14. Bxb5+ Nbc6 15. O-O O-O $11 {Chapter 4-2.c4 d4 3.b4 1.Nf3 d5 for Black part 1 2025 2024 And it is equal.}) (2. b3 Bf5 {[%csl Yb3] It's very important to understand that we develop the bishop to f5 only after White has played b3—never earlier! If White's pawn is still on b2, he might have Qb3 ideas, creating problems on b7.} 3. Bb2 e6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 {mainline, and after} (5. Nh4 {it's always important to check this idea.} Be4 $1 {it's extremely important to provoke f2-f3.} ({but not} 5... Bg6 $6 {[%csl Gf2] because now White's pawn is on f2!} 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Bg2 Bd6 8. O-O e5 9. c4 c6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gf2,Gg2][%cal Gg2d5] Bg2 works very well.}) 6. f3 Bg6 $15 {[%cal Gg6h5] And with the pawn on f3, this is a good position for Black.}) 5... h6 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 Bh7 {we come to a position that will be analyzed in Chapter 6. I suggest to start with this useful-prophylactic move. The idea of Bh7 is that e2-e4 or Nf3-d4 (more rarely) will never come with tempo.} 9. c4 {White's most common continuation.} a5 {[%csl Ga5] always useful move.} 10. a3 (10. a4 $2 {positional mistake.} Na6 $15 {[%cal Ga6b4] Nb4 next.}) 10... c6 {Famous position from the Reti / Reti-Slav. The position is playable, but White doesn’t have any dangerous ideas readily available. We should now examine how to react against the most popular continuations.} 11. Qc2 {the most common continuation.} (11. Bc3 {[%cal Gb3b4]} c5 $1 $132 {as a rule, when White plays Bc3 it becomes a good moment for c6-c5.}) (11. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gd1a1] Useful move. Very often White's plan will be Rc2-Qa1.} Re8 {[%csl Gb8,Ge8][%cal Gc4d5,Gc6d5,Gb8c6] Re8 more useful than Nbd7.}) (11. Ra2 {[%cal Gd1a1] very common continuation. White's idea is Qa1, and then slowly prepare b4 with Bc3-Rb1.} Qb6 $1 {very strong move.} 12. Qa1 Rd8 {[%csl Gb8] useful move. For the moment we don't want to decide the position of our Nb8.} 13. Bc3 Qa7 $1 $15 {[%cal Rb3b4,Gc6c5,Gb8c6] key move with the idea to prevent b3-b4. Maybe we will continue with c5-Nc6 next.}) 11... Re8 $5 $11) 2... Nf6 (2... Bf5 $6 {[%csl Gb2,Rf5] White's pawn is still on b2, so it's not a good moment for Bf5:} 3. c4 e6 4. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7,Rf5] this is why we play Bf5 only when White's pawn is already on b3, never earlier!}) 3. c4 {is White's main and most interesting move. It will be analyzed from Chapter 7 till Chapter 12.} (3. b3 Bf5 {[%csl Gf5] Once White plays b3, Bf5 becomes a very good option for us.} 4. Bb2 {natural, but now Black will be in time to play e6+h6.} (4. Be2 $5 {more interesting than the natural 4.Bb2, and it has been played in the recent Ding-Gukesh, World Championship Match 2024.} h6 {my recommendation. It's more important to prevent Nh4 than Ba3.} (4... e6 {also possible, but it allows} 5. Nh4 $5 {which could easily become tricky for us.}) 5. Ba3 $5 {interesting extra option.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ya3f8,Yd7f8] we prepare e6-Bxf8-Nxf8.} 6. c4 e6 7. Bxf8 Nxf8 $11) 4... e6 (4... h6 {also possible, but I don't like} 5. Bxf6 $5 exf6 6. Be2 {Where the nature of the position changes drastically.}) 5. Be2 (5. Nh4 {this will be interesting for White in the 4.Be2 line, but not here because of} Bg4 $1 $11 {[%csl Rb2,Ge2,Rf1] this is why 4.Be2 is more useful than 4.Bb2!}) 5... h6 $11 {[%csl Ge6,Gh6] Once Black plays e6 + h6 (useful against Nh4), all opening problems are solved. transposes in 4.Bb2, but Black is just fine.}) 3... e6 4. Nc3 b6 {My recommendation. 4...b6 keeps the game very independent compared to any opening against 1.d4 or 1.c4.} 5. cxd5 {will be analyzed in Chapter 11.} (5. d4 {will be analyzed in Chapter 12.} Bd6 {[%csl Gc8] Remember this move order: We shouldn’t rush with Bb7.} ({After the natural} 5... Bb7 {White has some extra ideas, for example:} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qa4+ $5 (7. Bb5+ $5)) 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Bb7 {we can consider this as the starting position of our Colle.} 8. b3 Re8 {[%csl Ge8] more useful than Nbd7.} 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Rc1 {has to be played at some point.} a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] we kill all White's Nb5 ideas.} 11. cxd5 (11. Na4 $6 {White's second most common move. It's dubious but concrete.} dxc4 12. bxc4 e5 $1 $15 {[%cal Rc4c5,Ge5e4] important move.}) 11... exd5 12. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3] Ne2-Ng3 standard plan for White, the only sensible plan I would say.} Ne4 13. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5]} g6 {[%cal Rg3f5] useful move against Nf5.} 14. Qc2 {and this is an important moment.} Rc8 {[%csl Gc7] important move to protect c7.} (14... Qe7 {looks natural, but now White has} 15. Ne5 $1 {and the game becomes more unclear. The main idea is that after} Nxe5 $2 {[%csl Rc7] we will have problems with c7:} 16. dxe5 $16)) (5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 {Starting position of Chapters 9 and 10.} 7. cxd5 {Statistically, this is White's most played move, but for several years now, no strong player has used it—simply because it poses no real problems for Black. In fact, it is White who needs to be precise.} (7. g3 {Now that White didn't include cxd5 exd5, Black can use this factor to his advantage by playing} dxc4 {not the only good move, but definitely the most interesting one.} 8. bxc4 e5 $1 9. Bg2 e4 {It's a position with only four games, but a very interesting one.}) 7... exd5 8. Rc1 (8. d4 a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] useful move against Nb5.} 9. g3 {White's only sensible deviation. The mix of b3 + d4 + g3 was considered interesting until 2022, but now it's clear that only Black can fight for something here.} Bd6 10. Bg2 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] preparing 0-0-0.} 11. O-O O-O-O $40 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] ;Chapter 9 2.e3-3.c4 e6 4.Nc3 b6 5.b3 side 1.Nf3 d5 for Black part 1 2025 2024 And it turns out that Black's h5-h4 attack is much faster than anything White can achieve on the queenside or in the center.}) 8... a6 {will be analyzed in Chapter 10.} 9. Ne2 {White's most common continuation.} c5 {[%cal Re2d4] First of all, we prevent Ned4.} 10. g3 (10. d4 $6 {logical move, but Black has a strong resource:} c4 $1 {as was played by the strong GM Motylev.} 11. bxc4 dxc4 12. Rxc4 b5 13. Rc2 Be4 14. Rc1 Bb4+ 15. Nd2 O-O $36 {This is not just compensation, but initiative. Abel-Motylev, 2024.}) 10... Bd6 11. Bg2 (11. d4 c4 $1 $15 {similar idea to Abel-Motylev.}) 11... b5 $11 {[%cal Gc5c4,Yd2d4] ;Chapter 10 2.e3-3.c4 e6 4.Nc3 b6 5.b3 7.Rc1 1.Nf3 d5 for Black part 1 2025 2024 Thanks to b6-b5, we can be certain that as soon as White plays d2-d4, we will always be able to respond with c5-c4, which is our key idea.} ({if Black just plays normal moves like} 11... O-O 12. O-O Re8 $6 {White is slightly better after} 13. d4 $1 $14 {[%cal Rc5c4] because Black doesn't have the c5-c4 idea.})) 5... exd5 {White can play 6.d4 transposing to the Colle system or 6.b3 transposing to the 5.b3 line analyzed in Chapter 6. In this chapter, we will analyze the independent options} 6. b4 $5 {Nowadays, this is White's trendiest continuation. In 2024, there were only 8 games in this position, but now there are more than 20, with many games played by 2600+ players.} (6. g3 {a serious move played more than 20 times by the strong and well-prepared GM Keymer Vincent} Bd6 {With White preparing to play Bg2, Black opts to postpone the development of Bb7, recognizing the potential opportunity to execute Ba6-Nc5 ideas in certain scenarios} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Yb8,Yc8,Ge8] waiting for White's next move} 9. Re1 $5 {useful prophylactic move against Ba6. This is the pet move of GM Keymer.} (9. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] Qc2 is misplaced and now we can play for c5-Nc6.} Bb7 $1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6] e defend d5 and are ready for c5-Nc6.} (9... Ba6 $6 {not a good idea here as White has Rd1} 10. Rd1 $1 $14 {Zwardon-Bartel 2022}) ({but not} 9... c5 $2 {immediately because of} 10. Ng5 $1 Bb7 11. Nxd5 $18)) (9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] natural continuation because White wants to develop Bc1.} Ba6 10. Re1 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5d3] with the idea Nc5-Nd3.}) 9... Nbd7 {[%csl Gc8] our Bc8 is still flexible: maybe it will go to a6, or maybe on b7.} 10. d3 a5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8a6] This might be simpler, with Ba6 next.} (10... Ba6 {my 2024 recommendation, it is also very good.})) 6... Be7 {Still my recommendation. I believe the most useful thing for us right now is to castle first, and only then decide how to react on the queenside against b4.} 7. Bb2 (7. Rb1 {This move was strong against 6...Bb7, but we have} Bf5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf5] big difference.}) (7. b5 {logical positional move, but after} a6 $1 $15 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ra2a4,Ga6b5] no time for a4 because Ra1 is hanging.}) 7... a6 $1 {[%cal Rb4b5] preventing b4-b5, which is positionally very good for White. Important to notice that 8.a4 is not possible because of Bxb4.} (7... O-O {was played in Kaasen-Reuker, 2024, but after} 8. b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5]} a6 9. a4 $14 {White has a long-term positional edge.}) 8. Qa4+ $1 {only critical move.} ({Black feels well if White just continues the development:} 8. Be2 $6 O-O 9. a3 c5 $1 10. bxc5 bxc5 $36 {and Black is the one with the initiative.}) 8... c6 9. b5 $1 $146 {the most critical move.} (9. d4 $2 {Eljanov-Schroeder, 2018.} b5 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Bf5-Nbd7-Nb6, and Black has a big positional advantage.}) 9... c5 $1 {strong move which allows us to solve all the problems.} 10. bxa6+ Bd7 11. Bb5 Rxa6 $132 *

