{[%evp 0,10,21,23,23,-16,-16,-47,-49,-39,0,0,21]} 1. Nf3 d5 {In Chapter 1, we will analyze White's minor sidelines at move 2.} 2. d3 {Not a move that poses theoretical problems, but we must decide what to play and which variations we are willing to enter. Move orders require some caution!} (2. e4 $2 {This fun gambit was bad a year ago, it's bad now, and it will still be bad 100 years from now!} dxe4 3. Ng5 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] we take the chance to develop our bishop to f5, from where it protects e4.} ({if we start with} 3... Nf6 $6 {then after} 4. Bc4 e6 {[%csl Gc8] our bishop has to stay on c8.} 5. Nc3 {White is only slightly worse, but we want more with Black against such a dubious line as 2.e4.}) 4. Nc3 (4. g4 Bg6 5. Bg2 h5 $1 6. Nxe4 hxg4 7. Qxg4 Nh6 $19 {[%cal Gh6f5] Nf5 next, for my engine this is already -2}) (4. Bc4 e6 5. d3 exd3 6. Qf3 {Firouzja-Giri, 2024 bullet.} dxc2 $1 $19 {immediately winning for Black.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bc4 (5. Qe2 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] we are ready for Nd4.} 6. Qb5 Qd7 $1 7. Qxb7 Rb8 8. Qa6 h6 $19 {[%cal Gc6d4] Nd4 next.}) 5... e6 6. f3 (6. Qe2 {also bad.} Qd4 $1 7. f3 (7. Nb5 Qd7 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Bb5 a6 10. Bxc6 Qxc6 $19) 7... exf3 8. Nxf3 Qb6 $17) 6... exf3 7. Qxf3 Nc6 $1 8. Nxf7 {It looks like we have fallen into White's trap, but after} Qd4 $3 {[%csl Gd4] White is lost. 8...Qd4 is a key move that refutes White's system.} 9. Nxh8 Qxc4 {[%csl Rh8] White will eventually lose Nh8.} 10. d3 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qh3 $19) (2. Nc3 {Only a truly creative player could go for it!} d4 {I like this principled move, which immediately highlights the drawback of White's last move.} 3. Ne4 (3. Nb1 {[%cal Ge2e3] Well, White will play e3 next and recover some tempi, but this cannot be a real problem.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] we prepare e5.} 4. e3 (4. e4 e5 5. Bb5 Qf6 $5 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ga7a6] Nge7-a6 next.}) 4... e5 5. exd4 exd4 6. Bb5 Nge7 (6... Qd5 $5 {also good option.}) 7. O-O a6 8. Bc4 (8. Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 Na5 $15 {[%cal Ga5b3,Gc8b7] Nxb3-Bb7 next and we will have the two bishops.}) 8... Ng6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Be7-00 next. We just have extra space for free.}) 3... e5 $1 4. e3 (4. Nxe5 $4 {of course not possible because of} Qd5 $19 {[%csl Re4,Re5][%cal Gd5e5,Gd5e4]}) (4. d3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gf7f5] Black can continue with normal development and just has a better position.}) 4... f5 5. Ng3 dxe3 $1 {Very important move to remember: without it, Black will be worse!} 6. dxe3 (6. fxe3 Bd6 $15 {just normal development moves next}) 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bd6 $36 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] Objectively equal, but Black has some small extra chances. A good plan could be Nc6 → Bd7 → 0-0-0 next.}) (2. b4 {now Black has many good moves, but I like} e5 {which keeps the game independent from any other opening—not just in theory, but also in the type of position—and allows us to fight for the initiative.} 3. Nxe5 {White should accept the challenge.} (3. a3 $2 {very bad move:} e4 4. Nd4 c5 5. bxc5 Bxc5 {[%cal Rc1b2,Gd8b6] strong center and better development. For example:} 6. e3 Nc6 7. Nb3 Bd6 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. d3 O-O $17) 3... Bxb4 {Now the position is quite unusual. We are likely to have more active pieces, but the only positional danger is White's extra central pawn. It's useful to study how the game could develop from here.} 4. c4 (4. e3 Nf6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bb2 {transposes in 4.Bb2.}) (4. Bb2 Nf6 5. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1] White wants to finish the development with Be2-00.} O-O 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. Nf3 {White wants to keep the knights.} (7. f4 $2 {positional mistake.} Nxe5 8. fxe5 Ne4 $15) (7. O-O Nxe5 8. Bxe5 Re8 {no problem for Black + easy play:} 9. d4 (9. Bb2 Bd6 10. Nc3 c6 $15 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gd6c7,Gd8d6]}) 9... Bf5 $11) 7... Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c4,Rc2c4] strong move that prevents c4.} 8. O-O Bd7 $5 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Ra2a4,Gd7a4,Gf8e8,Gb4f8,Rc2c4] another nice move. Our bishop could go to a4. We can continue then with Re8-Bf8 or with something else, depending on the situation.} 9. Ne5 Ba4 $132) 4... Ne7 $1 {[%cal Rd1a4] we need to defend against Qa4+.} ({Of course not} 4... Nf6 $2 {because of} 5. Qa4+ $18) 5. cxd5 (5. Qa4+ {now it doesn't make sense.} Nbc6 $15 {[%csl Ra4] Qa4 is misplaced.}) (5. Qb3 Bd6 6. Bb2 Na6 $1 7. cxd5 Nc5 8. Qf3 O-O $36 {[%cal Gc5a4] Na4 is a possible threat}) 5... Nxd5 $146 {[%csl Yb7,Yc7,Yd2,Ye2] Interesting position because we have better development but White has two central pawns.} 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. Bb2 Nc6 $1 {the strongest, but it's not an easy move to play OTB.} (8... c6 $6 9. O-O Nd7 {8...c6 followed by Nc6 could be a very natural game, but here White has the strong} 10. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 11. e4 $16 {[%cal Gd1b3] with Qb3 ideas.}) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Rb8 {[%csl Rb1,Rb2] White has big development problems.} 11. Nc3 {most natural move.} (11. Re1 {useful move, but now we can play} h5 $36 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) (11. d3 $4 {looks innocent, but it's a blunder.} Bg4 $18 {immediately winning for Black.}) 11... Bf8 {[%csl Rb2]} 12. Qc1 (12. Rb1 $6 Bf5 13. e4 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Bxe4 $15) 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Rxe2 14. Bxc6 h5 $11) 2... Nc6 {My new recommendation: By playing 2...Nc6, we can cut out a lot of lines.} (2... Nf6 3. Nbd2 c5 4. e4 Nc6 5. g3 e5 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O {It's fine for Black to play against the reversed KID, but if you're not a 1.d4 player, you might lack experience in these structures. That's why I want to offer something more independent.}) (2... g6 {this was my old recommendation, and it's also very fine.} 3. Nbd2 (3. g3 Bg7 {transposes in 1.Nf3 d5 part 2.}) 3... Bg7 4. e4 Nf6 (4... c6 {actually this transposes in a Caro Kann!}) 5. g3 (5. e5 {the best according to the engine.} Nfd7 6. d4 c5 7. c3 Nc6 $132 {interesting fight.}) 5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxe4 $5 {A good move that avoids the classical KID structures} 7. dxe4 Nc6 8. O-O a5 {a typical useful move, to take space on the queenside} 9. a4 (9. c3 Nd7 $1 10. Qc2 Nc5 11. Rd1 Qd3 $1 12. Qxd3 Nxd3 $15 {next Nxc1 with a slightly better endgame thanks to the bishops pair}) 9... Nd7 10. Nb3 $1 {best for White to fight for equality. White takes control of the c5 square.} (10. Nc4 b6 $36 {Fiorito-Bruzon, 2000.}) (10. Qe2 $2 b6 $1 11. Rd1 Ba6 12. Nc4 Qe8 13. Bf4 Bxb2 14. Rab1 Bg7 15. Bf1 Nc5 $19 {Grischuk-Artemiev, 2019.}) 10... e5 $11 {b6-Bb7 next with a good game}) 3. g3 {The most probable move to face, but after} (3. d4 {it's very unlikely that your opponent will play 3.d4, but in this case you could play} Bf5 $5 {transposing in a pure Jobava London: now you are playing with White, not with Black!}) (3. Nbd2 {White wants to play a reversed Philidor.} e5 4. e4 Nf6 5. Be2 Bd6 {This system (Bd3) is harmless when played by White against the Philidor, but since we are Black now, it easily equalizes.} 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 Re8 $132 {with the bishop on d6, we don't even need to play a5.} 8. b4 $6 a5 9. b5 Ne7 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Ye5][%cal Ge7g6,Yd6e5] this is possible thanks to the bishop on d6 that defends e5.}) 3... e5 4. Bg2 g6 (4... f6 $5 {good alternative.}) 5. O-O Bg7 {we transpose in 1.Nf3 d5 for Black part 2, and we basically don't need to study the 2.d3 line!} *

