{[%evp 0,26,19,29,14,-21,0,-16,-18,-4,-21,12,13,14,50,50,54,30,27,5,-1,4,5,4,4,-1,6,6,-16]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 {[%csl Gd4] My recommendation is to go for the ambitious and independent 2...d4. I also believe it is the most principled move for Black.} 3. e3 {White plays in Modern Benoni style.} Nc6 4. exd4 {[%csl Gd4] Now the game will revolve around the control of the d4 square.} (4. b4 {This gambit was first played in Takacs - Rubinstein, 1924, exactly 101 years ago! Despite being objectively dubious, it is still occasionally played today—even by players over 2400.} dxe3 5. fxe3 Nxb4 6. d4 {White's most common continuation.} (6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. d4 Bd7 8. Qb3 e5 {the simplest.} (8... Na5 $5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Yg7g6] is also good, with c5 or g6 next.}) 9. d5 (9. dxe5 {strongest according to the engines, but it means that Black is doing too well:} Nh6 10. Be2 Bc5 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8e7] 00-Qe7 next. It's equal for the engine, but every human would take Black.}) 9... Nb4 10. Nc3 Na6 11. Nxe5 Nf6 $17 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Ga6c5] Bd6-Nc5-00 next, with a huge positional advantage.}) (6. Nc3 {Black has a lot of good continuations. The simplest one is} c5 7. d4 g6 8. d5 Bg7 9. Bd2 Nh6 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) 6... e5 $1 {Black's key move. If you think this is a typical computer move, you’re completely wrong—Rubinstein already found it in the first recorded game back in 1924!} 7. a3 (7. Nxe5 Bf5 8. Na3 Bd6 9. Nf3 (9. Be2 $146 {engine's first move.} Bxe5 10. O-O Ne7 11. Qa4+ Nbc6 12. dxe5 O-O $15 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gc6e5,Yf5e6] Ng6 (with Be6 first) -Ncxe5 next and Black has a good positional advantage.}) 9... c5 $17 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] Nf6-00 next. The material is equal, but Black's pieces are much more active.}) 7... Nc6 $1 {the right continuation.} ({In the game Sochacki - Lagarde, 2024, Black was unaware of the strongest continuation.} 7... e4 $6 8. axb4 exf3 9. c5 $1 fxg2 10. Bxg2 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 $36 {[%eval 0,0] according to the engine, but it's much easier to play it with White.}) 8. d5 {White's most popular move.} (8. Nc3 exd4 9. exd4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] simple play: Be7-00 next.} 10. Be2 Be7 11. O-O O-O {White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn, for example:} 12. Kh1 Bg4 13. Be3 Re8 14. Bg1 Bf8 $15) (8. Be2 {Black is better after many moves:} e4 ({the simple} 8... Be7 $15 {is also good.}) (8... exd4 9. exd4 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] Bg7-Nf6-00 next, we just have an extra pawn.}) 9. Nfd2 f5 $15 {[%cal Gd8g5] Qg5 next probably.}) 8... Nb8 $5 {the simplest way in my opinion.} (8... e4 {is equally strong.} 9. dxc6 (9. Nfd2 Ne5 10. Nxe4 Qh4+ 11. Nf2 Nf6 $17) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 exf3 11. gxf3 bxc6 $15) 9. Nxe5 Bd6 10. Nf3 Nf6 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gf8e8] 00-Nbd7-Re8 next. Equal material but positional advantage and easy play for Black.}) (4. d3 {A move that was played a few months ago against my good friend Lodici, a good Italian GM.} e5 5. exd4 exd4 6. Be2 {GM Lodici played here the natural 6...Bb4+, but I believe that the strongest continuation is} Nge7 $1 7. O-O Ng6 $15 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Rc1f4] Be7-0-0 next, and Black is simply better since White has no counterplay. The knight on g6 is very well-placed, as, for example, it prevents White from developing with Bf4.}) 4... Nxd4 5. Nxd4 (5. d3 {very rare and for a good reason.} Nxf3+ 6. Qxf3 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8h6,Ge8g8,Gh6f5] the simplest. Bg7-Nh6-00-Nf5 next.} ({or} 6... e5 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Be2 Nf5 $15 {Bd6-00 next})) 5... Qxd4 6. Nc3 ({difficult to imagine White playing without Nc3, but there are some extra ideas, for example:} 6. d3 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gh6f5,Yf5d4] the knight will normally go to f5.} 7. Be2 Nf5 8. O-O {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3] was played in the recent game Flores-Korobov, Olympiad 2024. White's idea is to continue with Bd2-Bc3.} (8. Nd2 $6 {[%cal Gd2f3] Looks logical, as the knight moves to f3 to control the d4 square, but Black now has the time to develop in an ideal way:} g6 9. Nf3 Qd6 10. Bd2 Bg7 11. Bc3 O-O $15 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gc7c5] b6-Bb7-c5 next. Black has a good positional advantage.}) 8... e5 {the simplest:} 9. Bd2 Bc5 10. Bc3 Qd6 11. Nd2 Bd4 $11 {equal position.}) 6... c6 {[%csl Yc3,Gc6] very useful move to limit Nc3.} ({we cannot start with the immediate} 6... Nh6 $2 {because of} 7. Nd5 $1 $16) 7. d3 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5] Don't be afraid of Bxh6, as it is simply bad for White. The correct knight development is Nh6 → Nf5.} 8. Be3 (8. Bxh6 $2 {positional mistake.} gxh6 $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh8g8,Gc8f5] We have the bishop pair and excellent piece activity, controlling many key squares. We can continue with Bf5 → Rg8.}) (8. h3 Nf5 9. g4 {Concrete idea. It's objectively dubious, but you need to know how to handle it properly.} Qe5+ $1 {[%cal Gf5d4] freeing the d4 square for the knight.} (9... Nh4 $2 {would be a mistake now because Whtie plays} 10. Qe2 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1c1] Be3-000 next, with a big advantage for White.}) 10. Qe2 (10. Ne4 $2 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh7h5] just big positional advantage for Black. Sometimes, we can continue with h7-h5, for example:} 11. f4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qd8 13. Bg2 g6 $17 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gh7h5] Bg7-h5 next, and Black had a big advantage in Naiditsch-Bauer, 2011.}) 10... Qxe2+ 11. Nxe2 {now White controls the d4 square, but we have} Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5] h5 is our idea.} 12. Ng3 $146 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Rh7h5] White's best, with the idea to prevent h5, but we are slightly better after} (12. Be3 $2 h5 $1 $15) 12... e5 13. Be3 Bb4+ $15 {[%cal Ge8g8] 0-0 next, we are slightly better and we have very easy play.}) (8. Be2 Nf5 9. g4 {similar to the 8.h3 Nf6 9.g4 line, but now our reaction is different as we no longer have Qe5+.} (9. O-O h5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] prophylactic move against g4 and we will continue with g6-Bg7 next.} (9... g6 $2 10. g4 $1 $14)) 9... Nh4 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Yh7h5] we can continue with g6-Bg7 or with the concrete h5! Compared to the 8.h3 variation, here White doesn't have the Qe2-Be3-000 plan.} 10. Rg1 {[%cal Gc1e3] prophylactic move against Ng2. Now White is ready for Be3.} (10. Be3 Ng2+ 11. Kd2 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Rd2,Gf8] White has the center, but we have the two bishops and Kd2 is not safe.}) 10... Qd6 $1 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gd6h2] prophylactic move against Be3. (but Qxh2 is also a pleasant threat :) )} (10... e5 $6 {natural but bad:} 11. Be3 Qd8 12. d4 $14 {White's pieces are better placed for the soon-to-arise symmetrical structure.}) 11. h3 $1 $146 {White's best continuation.} (11. f4 $2 h5 $17) (11. Rg3 {[%csl Rg3] Rg3 is misplaced and we can feel it in the following line:} e5 12. Be3 f5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Yg4f5,Yh4f5] if gxf5 we will play Nxf5 gaining a tempo against the misplaced Rg3.}) 11... h6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5] we prepare the positional move g5.} 12. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] the best because Qd2-000 is a serious idea.} Qh2 $1 {[%cal Gh4g2] with Ng2+ idea.} 13. Kd2 Ng2 14. Qf1 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Qc7 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] g6-Bg7 next. We are preferable thanks to the two bishops.}) 8... Qd8 {the main move. It's a good one, but not the only one.} (8... Qf6 $5 {it's very rare, but it also deserves attention.}) 9. d4 (9. Bxh6 gxh6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Bg7 → 0-0 next. Our two bishops fully compensate for the slight structural damage.} 10. d4 Bg7 11. d5 Bf5 $11) (9. Be2 Nf5 10. O-O Nxe3 11. fxe3 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8h6,Ge8g8] Bh6-00 next}) 9... Nf5 10. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Gd2e3] Important move, as White should be ready to recapture on e3 with the queen.} (10. Be2 $6 Nxe3 11. fxe3 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8h6,Ge8g8] Bg7 or Bh6 and 00 next}) 10... g6 {White can now decide whether to castle short or long.} 11. Be2 {safer.} (11. O-O-O $6 {more ambitious, but objectively worse.} Bg7 12. Be2 Nxe3 $1 {first, we want to see how White plans to recapture.} (12... O-O {This is Black's most common move, and it was also my 2024 recommendation. However, I now see it differently—we can delay castling for a few moves.}) 13. Qxe3 $146 (13. fxe3 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b5] 00-b5 next.} 14. h4 $6 {[%csl Ge8] h4 is nothing when our king is still on e8:} h5 $17) 13... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] we prepare b5.} 14. d5 $1 {[%csl Gg7] the best, but now our Bg7 becomes very strong.} (14. h4 $6 h5 $17 {[%cal Gg7h6]}) 14... O-O 15. dxc6 {the start of a concrete line.} Qa5 16. c7 Qxc7 17. Nd5 Qa5 18. Nxe7+ Kh8 19. Nxc8 Rfxc8 $17 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gb7b5] this is not compensation but advantage.}) 11... Bg7 12. Rd1 {[%csl Gd4] White must defend d4.} (12. O-O-O Nxe3 {transposes in 11.000.}) 12... O-O 13. O-O Qa5 $36 {[%cal Ga5b4,Gf8d8] We are not in a hurry to capture on e3, as we will do it at the best possible moment. For now, we have ideas like Rd8 or Qb4, creating additional threats.} *

