{[%evp 0,38,21,21,21,11,16,-31,-30,-30,-35,-31,22,23,19,22,31,14,7,-53,-35,-26,-36,-43,-60,-60,22,22,98,-4,34,29,64,29,50,60,28,-80,-40,7,-4]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. g3 (3. d3 Nc6 4. g3 {transposes to 3.g3} (4. e4 $6 {just a bad strategical decision. White transposes to a bad version of the reversed, closed old indian.} e5 5. Be2 Bb4+ 6. Nbd2 a5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Ne1 {as I can understand the only possible plan for White is the f2-f4 idea} O-O 9. a3 Bd6 10. g3 Bh3 11. Ng2 Nd7 12. f4 f5 $17)) 3... Nc6 4. Bg2 e5 {The starting position of the chapter. White has two approaches: to play with 0-0 and allow Black to play e4, or to play the classical d3 setup.} 5. O-O $5 {It is an interesting line .White wants to play d3 on the next move, so he has avoided the 5.d3 Bb4+ line.} (5. d3 {I think here it is easier to play for Black, because we don't have to commit all-in, we can get a pleasant position, because the structure is dubious for White in general.} Bb4+ 6. Bd2 $1 {The best.} (6. Nfd2 $6 {is just bad, but a good reaction is} h5 $1 $15 {Because the knight left f3, this is stronger.}) (6. Nbd2 $6 {is also not great, but now please remember the next move.} a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ra2a3,Rb2b4] Prophylaxis move against a3-b4.} (6... Nf6 $6 {Don't start with this move, because after} 7. a3 $1 $132 {[%cal Gb2b4] If Black retreats the bishop, White will play b4.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {There have been some games, but Black is just slightly better.} 8. a3 (8. Ne1 O-O 9. Nc2 Bc5 $15 {It is a good version of Benoni.}) 8... Be7 {also 8...Bd6 is good, it is a matter of taste.} 9. b3 {White slowly prepares b4.} (9. Ne1 {Against this plan, I like} O-O 10. Nc2 a4 {But there are a lot of good moves.} 11. Nb4 {Typical idea.} Nb8 $5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc7c6] Black plans c6 next and the knight will be useless.} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 {You can play} (13. cxd5 {is the best, but it is not critical.} Nd7 $15 {[%cal Gd7f6] Nf6 next.}) 13... h5 $40 {[%cal Ga8a6] With a big advantage.}) (9. Rb1 {is met with} a4 $15 {[%cal Rb2b4,Ga4b3] And whenever White plays b4, you take it and have a better structure.}) 9... O-O 10. Rb1 Nd7 {But we have our own plans.} 11. Ne1 Nc5 12. Nc2 {Many good moves for Black.} Bg4 {[%cal Rc5d3] is one of them, with idea of Nxd3.} 13. Nf3 {Logical.} (13. Qe1 Qd7 $15) 13... h5 $5 {I like this, to get some space.} 14. h3 Bf5 15. b4 {Whenever White plays b4, the reaction is} Na4 $15 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ga4c3] And the knight gets to c3.}) 6... a5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bxb4 {The only critical option of the whole 5.d3 line.} (8. Bg5 $6 {Just positionally bad plan.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 {White gave the bishop pair for nothing.} 10. a3 Be7 11. Nbd2 O-O $17 {[%cal Rd2e4,Gf6g6] The knight on e4 cannot do anything.}) (8. Na3 {is the main move, with idea Nc2, but I don't like it.} O-O 9. Nc2 (9. Nb5 $6 {White goes for a wrong direction} Re8 10. e3 Bf5 $1 11. e4 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 $17 {0-1 Speelman,J (2555)-Nakamura,H (2601) Monarch Assurance 13th Port Erin 2004 (6)}) 9... Bd6 {You can keep the bishops.} (9... Bxd2 $5 {also good.} 10. Qxd2 Qd6 $15) 10. b3 {Typical to play for b4, without allowing a4.} (10. a3 $6 {is as usual met with} a4 11. Nb4 Ne7 {c5 is a threat, that's why White plays} 12. c5 Bxc5 13. Nxe5 {A lot of moves are good.} Ng6 $5 14. Nxg6 hxg6 $15) (10. e3 {You can play as you want.} Bf5 {Strong move.} 11. Be1 Bc5 12. exd4 {You can take with the bishop or} exd4 $15 {Black is slightly better.}) 10... Re8 11. a3 e4 $5 {Not the only move, but a good one.} 12. dxe4 Nxe4 13. Be1 (13. Ncxd4 $2 {is a mistake, because of} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Be5 $15) 13... Nc3 14. Bxc3 dxc3 $36 {and Black has the initiative.}) (8. e3 {is also not a problem.} O-O 9. exd4 {You can take back with the pawn, if you don't want to study, or} Nxd4 {You can take with the knight.} 10. Nxd4 {White should take on d4, but after} (10. Nxe5 $2 {is a mistake, because of} Re8 $1 {Tactical problems.} 11. f4 {is met with} (11. Nf3 Ne2+ $17 {Qd3 next.}) 11... Ng4 $1 {Fantastic move.} 12. Nxg4 Ne2+ $17) 10... Qxd4 11. Bc3 Bxc3 12. Nxc3 c6 $15 {It is just slightly better for Black.}) 8... axb4 $1 9. Nbd2 {The best.} (9. a3 {is met with} Qe7 {[%csl Rb1] and White has to play Nbd2 sooner or later, that transposes to what we will see.}) 9... Qe7 $5 {That's why I prefer to start with Qe7, against a3 ideas.} (9... O-O {In the majority of games, including Kacharava-Ivic from 2024, Black played castle but after} 10. a3 $1 {White has very easy play.} bxa3 11. Rxa3 Rxa3 12. bxa3 $11 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gf1b1] It's 0.00 for the engine, but I don't like it for Black.}) 10. Re1 $5 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gd4e3,Ge1e3] is the most interesting, with idea e3 and recapture with the rook.} (10. a3 {Some player tried this move in 2024, and it looks like a blunder, but it is also possible strangely enough!} bxa3 11. Qb3 {is the idea, because the rook is pinned.} Ra6 $1 $146 12. Rxa3 {is the best, and now logical moves:} (12. bxa3 $2 {Mistake.} Nd7 $17 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5a4,Ga4c3] Bad position for White.}) 12... Rb6 13. Qc2 Nb4 14. Qa4+ Nd7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7c5] If we finish development, Black is slightly better.} 15. c5 $1 {is the engine offer.} Qxc5 16. Nc4 Ra6 17. Qb3 {And some compensation exists, but not full.} O-O 18. Rxa6 Nxa6 19. Ra1 Qe7 $15 {Should be slightly better for Black.}) (10. e3 {Immediately is not so good.} dxe3 11. fxe3 O-O $15 {The pawn structure is just weak.}) 10... O-O 11. e3 dxe3 12. Rxe3 {[%cal Gd3d4] This is an important line, because White's idea is to push d4.} Qd6 {We remove the queen from the e-file.} 13. Nb3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White insists.} Be6 $5 {[%cal Rd3d4,Ge6c4] But I think this is a good solution.} (13... Kh8 $6 {If you are slow for one move:} 14. d4 $14 {And White is having an advantage.}) 14. d4 {Still it is critical.} Bxc4 15. dxe5 {Now the line is forced.} Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Nd5 17. Ree1 {The critical option.} Nde7 $5 {That's why I prefer some retreating move like this.} (17... Rxa2 {I am a bit scared of this, because after} 18. Nfd2 $13 {The lines are very concrete.}) 18. Nfd2 Be6 $11 {[%csl Ra2] Engine says that it is -0.05, but if I would have to choose one side, it is for sure Black, because of the a2 pawn being a long term weakness, but engine plays somehow Nc1 and says that it is okay.}) 5... e4 $1 {Black should play concretely, and it is a matter of who is prepared better here. But after this chapter, it will be you, since we cover everything.} (5... Nf6 {Don't play this move, because after} 6. d3 {White tricked us, since} Bb4 {[%csl Re1,Gg1] doesn't come with check.}) 6. Ne1 h5 $1 {The key move. This is the only justification for the target on e4 that we created.} (6... Nf6 {The center is vulnerable and White can play} 7. d3 $1 {And anyways Black has to try to play h5.}) 7. d3 $1 {The best move for White.} (7. Bxe4 $2 {is a mistake, but of course, we need to know it, since White won a pawn.} Bh3 8. Qb3 {The best.} (8. Ng2 Qd7 $17 {[%cal Gh5h4] h4 next with a decisive attack.}) (8. Bg2 Qd7 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gh5h4] And I think that objectively White's position is lost. Engine says that only 9.e4 is -1.50, but I think that also there it is lost.} 9. Nf3 {was played in one game.} h4 {And it's game over for White.} 10. d3 hxg3 11. fxg3 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 O-O-O $19 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf6g4] Pawn down, but look at the pieces. It's -3 something.}) 8... Qc8 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gc8] Useful move to defend the pawn and the queen can later on join the attack.} 9. Qb5 {Van Wely tried this in the game with Sadwhani.} (9. Ng2 {is again met with} h4 $17 {With big attack.}) (9. d3 $17 {is the best, but you can at minimum take the exchange and be better.}) 9... Nf6 $1 {Good reply.} 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 {And now a strong novelty would have been} c5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gd7g4,Yg4h3,Rf3c6] with the idea of introducing both Bg4 and Bh3, without allowing the check on c6.} (12... h4 $2 {was played in the game, but after} 13. d3 $13 {White is more or less fine.}) 13. e3 (13. d3 Bg4 $19 {[%csl Re2] e2 falls and White is lost.}) 13... Bd6 {Black can just finish development.} 14. exd4 cxd4 15. d3 O-O {2 pawns down, but look at the pieces.} 16. Nd2 {Only move, otherwise it's -3.} Bg4 17. Qh1 Be2 $17 {Black can at minimum win the exchange, and have the better pieces.}) (7. h4 $4 {was played in the game Paravyan-Mithraba, in February 2024, but it is just a losing move.} g5 $1 8. hxg5 Qxg5 {The strongest.} 9. d3 Qg7 $19 {[%cal Gh5h4] h4 next and it is just a -3 position.}) 7... e3 $1 {The only good move, you need to destroy the pawn structure.} (7... h4 $2 {Don't play this move, because after} 8. dxe4 hxg3 9. fxg3 $1 $14 {White can actually be slightly better here, so you see it is important to know the theory.}) 8. fxe3 {The critical move and now} (8. Nf3 {was played in the game Harika-Kacharava, but it is not critical.} exf2+ 9. Rxf2 Nf6 $17 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gf6g4] Black is just structurally better.}) 8... h4 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gh4g3] Only when the structure is destroyed, so after hxg3 there is no fxg3 option. There are 14 games and only 4 human games. It White follows the engine lines, they can be fine, but over the board it is very difficult to play.} 9. exd4 {The most common move between humans.} (9. Bxc6+ {is another engine recommendation.} bxc6 10. Qa4 {Again, Black has a lot of good moves, I will check the simplest.} Bd7 11. exd4 hxg3 12. hxg3 Bd6 {Black has the initiative. Engine shows a very precise path for White to achieve a complicated game} 13. Nf3 c5 14. Qa5 Bh3 15. Rf2 Nf6 16. Bf4 Rh5 $13 {and all 3 results are possible now}) (9. Nf3 {is another logical move, but engine doesn't like it.} hxg3 10. hxg3 Bd6 11. exd4 Bxg3 12. d5 {Now you can play many moves, but} Nd4 $1 {seems strong.} 13. Nc3 {The only way, and again a crazy line:} (13. Nxd4 $4 {leads to mate.} Bh2+ 14. Kf2 Qh4+ $19 {with mate in 5.}) 13... Bg4 14. Qa4+ b5 15. cxb5 Nxf3+ 16. Rxf3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Kf8 $36 {[%csl Rg1] Equal material, but look at White's king.}) (9. gxh4 {Engine recommends taking on h4, but who will find it?} Qxh4 10. Bxc6+ $1 {is the idea.} (10. Nf3 $2 {Not this, because} Qh5 $17) 10... bxc6 11. Nf3 {But it is very unlogical play from White.} Qh5 12. exd4 Bh3 $13 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8f6] Engine says it is equal, but it's easy play for Black.}) 9... hxg3 {And now nobody found the only good move.} 10. d5 $1 $146 {Only move.} (10. Bf4 {was played in the game Jahncke-Yankelevich.} gxh2+ 11. Kh1 Nxd4 $1 12. e3 {Black retreated to e6, but I think that} Nf5 $1 $17 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g5] is stronger. f6-g5 and the position is lost for White.}) (10. hxg3 $2 {was played in the games Burmakin-Van den Doel and Soham-Lavrinenkov.} Qxd4+ $1 $146 {A stronger recapture than with the knight.} 11. e3 Qd6 12. Qf3 Nf6 $17 {[%cal Gc6e5] Complicated position, but Black has a very easy initiative and -1 evaluation.}) 10... Bg4 $5 {But I like this more.} (10... gxh2+ $5 {is one good option.} 11. Kh1 Nd4 $36) (10... Rxh2 {is also a good move.} 11. Nf3 {Logical and now fantastic} Nd4 $3 {Very interesting.} 12. Bf4 $1 {Only move.} (12. Nxh2 $4 {This is just mate after} Qh4 $1 13. Nf3 Nxf3+ 14. Rxf3 Qh2+ 15. Kf1 Bh3 $19 {[%cal Gh2h1] Game over.}) 12... Bg4 13. Bxg3 Bxf3 14. exf3 (14. Bxf3 $4 {is bad, because of} Rh6 $1 $19 {Winning position.}) 14... Rh6 $36 {-0.10, also very interesting.}) 11. Nf3 (11. dxc6 $4 {is just game over after} Bc5+ $19 {Either mate or White loses the queen.}) 11... Bc5+ 12. e3 gxh2+ 13. Kh1 Nf6 {And again taking the piece is a mistake.} 14. Nc3 {Important with idea to meet} (14. dxc6 $4 {is again a losing mistake.} Nh5 {with Ng3 mate ideas.} 15. Qe1 Bd6 $19 {Game over.}) 14... Nh5 {with} 15. Ne2 {To cover the g3 square.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] We are ready for Nf5.} 16. e4 {to stop it.} Ng6 {The position is very complicated and interesting, for example:} 17. d4 {is the best.} Be7 18. Bd2 {is the best, but who will understand it?} (18. Be3 $2 {is a mistake.} Nh4 $17 {Black is better.}) 18... Nh4 19. Qa4+ {I think it is a good moment to stop, because we are very far away from official theory, and Black has more than one good move always.} Bd7 $13 {or b5, with complicated play.} *

