{[%evp 0,34,20,20,27,0,0,0,9,-8,-1,0,0,-54,-54,-54,-54,-54,-54,-58,-64,-60,-26,-24,-18,-18,4,4,-4,2,2,2,2,2,23,2,2]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. b4 f6 4. e3 {The main move.} (4. Bb2 $6 {is not impressive.} e5 5. a3 {You have a lot of moves.} (5. e3 dxe3 6. fxe3 Bxb4 $15 {No compensation for White.}) 5... c5 $15 {at least, and Black is slightly better, no need to investigate.}) (4. Qa4+ $2 {was tried in some games, but it is also not so great.} Bd7 5. Qb3 {The queen is not always useful here.} e5 6. e3 c5 7. bxc5 {This was the game Malakhatko-Tulchynskyi, Kiev 2023.} Bxc5 $1 $146 {Strong novelty.} 8. Ba3 {is probably the best.} (8. Qxb7 $2 Nc6 $19 {Winning position for Black, too much development.}) 8... b6 {To reinforce c5.} 9. exd4 exd4 10. Be2 Ne7 11. O-O Bc6 $17 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge8g8,Ge7g6] Black finishes development, and the position is just better.}) (4. Na3 {Here I made some changes:} e5 5. Nc2 c5 {I like this more, to not give White easy play.} (5... Na6 $5 {In the original database, this was my recommendation, and I also won a nice game in Gibraltar 2020 using it, but I found an idea for White.} 6. a3 {I analysed and after} c5 7. d3 $5 $146 {is a novelty. After which White plays in Benko style.} cxb4 8. axb4 Nxb4 9. g3 $44 {The evaluation is equal, but I don't want to allow White such easy play.}) 6. bxc5 Bxc5 7. d3 {And now Black can finish development:} Ne7 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 Na6 10. O-O Bg4 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7] Qd7 next and Black is doing absolutely fine. So this is my new recommendation.}) (4. d3 {was tried also in some recent games, for example Giri-Kazakouski, from just one month ago.} e5 5. a3 {White's idea is to play a Reversed Benoni, where the plan of b2-b4 is achieved.} g5 $5 {But now I think that this is a very good option, first of all, because there are only 2 games here, so it is unlikely that your opponent will be prepared, and second of all, it is a strong move and it makes things clear immediately.} (5... a5 {Last time I recommended this move, but I feel that more and more players will start investigating it.}) 6. g3 {is also a normal move, now I like} (6. e3 g4 $146 {It's a novelty.} 7. Nh4 {This is the best for White, but it is very unlikely that a human will play like this.} (7. Nfd2 {can be met in the same style:} a5 8. b5 h5 {To take some space.} 9. exd4 exd4 10. h3 Bh6 $36 {[%cal Ge8f7,Gg8e7] looks good for Black.}) 7... dxe3 $5 {was my idea.} 8. fxe3 a5 9. b5 f5 {And even though the engine thinks it is equal, I am more than ready to play it:} 10. g3 Be7 11. Bb2 Bxh4 12. gxh4 Qxh4+ 13. Kd2 Nd7 $13 {I understand that White has their own trumps, but the position is for 3 results, and White can also lose in a few moves.}) (6. h3 {with idea to prevent g4.} Ne7 7. e3 dxe3 8. fxe3 Bg7 $5 {For a fighting game.} (8... Nf5 {is a very good option, if you are fine with a draw.} 9. Nxe5 {is the best, and the game will end in a repetition after} (9. Kf2 {is met with} h5 $15 {Black is better.}) 9... fxe5 10. Qh5+ Kd7 11. Qg4 Ke8 12. Qh5+ $11) 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be2 {And now a very good move:} f5 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6] Because White cannot capture the g5 pawn.} 11. Bb2 {Logical and now} (11. Nxg5 $4 {This loses material.} h6 12. Nf3 e4 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Rf3] Both knights are hanging.}) 11... f4 $1 {[%cal Ge7f5] Strong move, the knight goest to f5.} 12. exf4 gxf4 $36 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Ge7f5,Gb8c6,Gd8d6,Gc6e7] It's equal for the engine, but I am very happy to play it. h3 was a big weakening move.}) 6... a5 7. b5 Nd7 {To get the c5 square.} 8. e3 Nc5 9. exd4 exd4 {And White needs to find a strong move to not be worse:} 10. Ra2 $1 {But now Black can play as he wishes:} (10. Bg2 $2 {The key point is that this is not recommendable, because of} Qe7+ 11. Kf1 Bf5 $17 {[%csl Rd3] And problems with d3 pawn.}) 10... Bf5 11. Be2 {Again only move, and Black has a lot of good moves.} Ne7 $36 {[%cal Gf5h3,Gd8d7] I think everybody would choose Black here.}) 4... e5 5. c5 {is the main move, but here nothing changed.} (5. Qb3 $6 a5 6. b5 c5 $15) (5. exd4 $6 e4 6. Qe2 Qe7 7. Ng1 Nc6 $15) (5. b5 Ne7 {But I think now this is easier for us to play. It is also a rare move, only 3 games.} (5... Bb4 $5 $146 {Last time I suggested this move.}) 6. a4 {The best waiting move.} (6. exd4 $2 {is a mistake, because of} e4 $17 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Rd1e2] And very important that White doesn't have Qe2 to pin the pawn.}) (6. Bd3 {Also engine style move.} Nd7 $1 {is a strong idea, with the point of} 7. exd4 Nc5 $1 {Thanks to the pin.} 8. Be2 {The best.} (8. dxc5 $4 {is the losing mistake.} Qxd3 $19 {-3 position.}) 8... exd4 9. d3 g5 {I like this move gaining space.} 10. O-O {The best, and after} (10. Bb2 {is not scary, just} Ne6 $36 {To defend it.}) 10... Ng6 11. Nfd2 a6 $36 {I stopped here, but it's clear that the position is very interesting for Black.}) (6. c5 $146 {Strange novelty by the engine.} a6 $15 {And it's -0.30 after the only good move Bb2, but I guess we can play this.}) 6... Ng6 7. exd4 {And only exd4 now, because the knight left the e-file.} exd4 {But we can take and Black's position is fine.} (7... e4 $6 {So this is not great now, because of} 8. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Re4,Re8][%cal Ge2e8] White's idea.}) 8. g3 Bf5 $5 {I like this move.} (8... Bb4 {is also possbile, and it leads to some equal endgame after} 9. Bg2 Qe7+ 10. Qe2 c5 11. Ba3 a5 12. Bxb4 axb4 13. d3 Bf5 14. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $11 {But I prefer more 8...Bf5, to be honest.}) 9. Qe2+ {looks necessary.} (9. Bg2 {is met with} Bd3 $1 $17 {And White is worse, of course.}) 9... Kf7 10. Bg2 Bc5 {Easy play.} 11. O-O Re8 12. Qd1 {Only move.} Bd3 13. Bb2 {is the best for Black.} (13. Re1 {99% of players will play this without thinking too much.} Nd7 $132 {Absolutely fine position for Black.}) 13... Bxf1 (13... Qd6 {If you don't want to take the exchange, this is also playable.}) (13... Be2 $5 {also interesting, to first include this and then take.} 14. Qb3 Bxf1 15. Kxf1 c6 $13) 14. Kxf1 {Engine thinks that White has full compensation here.} d3 15. Ne1 c6 $13 {We can also play this position, it's 0.00.}) 5... a5 $1 {The best.} 6. Qa4+ (6. Bb5+ $6 c6 7. Bc4 axb4 8. Nxe5 {a wrong but important to know line} fxe5 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qxe5+ Qe7 11. Qxh8 Nf6 12. d3 $1 {only move to stay in the game} (12. Bb2 $2 {White is lost immediately after this} Be6 13. Bxe6 Qxe6 14. g4 Nbd7 15. g5 Ne4 16. Bxd4 O-O-O 17. f3 Nxg5 18. O-O Bh6 {0-1 Stella,A (2463)-Bertagnolli,A (2329) Ortisei Server24 op 2nd 2013 (4)}) 12... Be6 13. Nd2 Nbd7 14. O-O $1 $146 (14. a3 $2 dxe3 15. fxe3 b3 $19 {0-1 Panjwani,R (2440)-So,W (2744) Edmonton 9th 2014 (3)}) 14... dxe3 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe6 Qxe6 17. dxe4 exf2+ 18. Kh1 O-O-O 19. Qb2 Bxc5 20. Bg5 Re8 21. Bh4 Qe5 $15) (6. Nxe5 $2 {a dubious but entertaining move played in the famous game Van Wely-Kramnik} fxe5 7. Qh5+ Kd7 8. Qf5+ Ke7 9. Qxe5+ Be6 10. Bc4 Qd7 11. b5 {½-½ Van Wely,L (2681)-Kramnik,V (2799) Amber-rapid 17th Nice 2008 (7) preventing Nc6} Kf7 $1 12. Bxe6+ Qxe6 13. Qxc7+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. exd4 Be7 $17 {I am not sure if Black is objectively winning here, but for sure he has very good winning chances}) (6. Bc4 axb4 7. Nxe5 {even worse than in the 7.Bb5+ line, as now Black will have the c6 square to escape with his king!} fxe5 8. Qh5+ Kd7 9. Qf5+ Kc6 $1 $19) (6. Bb2 {only 2 games, but actually the 2nd best move for White} dxe3 7. fxe3 axb4 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bc4 e4 10. Nfd2 f5 11. a3 Qg5 $13 {unclear new position, evaluated with 0.00 by engine}) 6... Bd7 {My recommendation now, because I realised that it just makes the variation empty for White.} (6... c6 $6 {the worst between the four logical moves} 7. Bc4 Na6 8. a3 $14) (6... Nc6 {interesting possibility with only 10 games} 7. b5 Nb4 8. a3 Nd5 9. Qc2 $5 {suggested by Cheparinov and probably White's most interesting option, that has the simple ideas of defending the c5 pawn and preventing sometimes e5-e4} (9. exd4 exd4 10. Qxd4 Qe7+ 11. Be2 Qxc5 $11) 9... Nh6 {the position is playable for both sides. I didn't choose this as our main line because here, White has a lot of interesting possible moves, but still, objectively, Black should be able to equalize everywhere}) (6... Qd7 $5 {Interesting if Black is looking for a complicated game. I will suggest you two different directions in the main line, and the most brave players could try to use them to play for the full point, as also White is running some strategic (and tactical) risk here} 7. Bb5 $1 (7. b5 Bxc5 8. Bc4 Qd6 $36 {Nd7 next}) 7... c6 8. Bc4 {and here Black has two good directions in my opinion} Ne7 (8... Na6 9. exd4 (9. a3 axb4 10. axb4 Nc7 11. Qxa8 Nxa8 12. Rxa8 b5 $1 $15) (9. O-O {not critical} Ne7 {here Black has a good game} 10. d3 (10. a3 axb4 11. Bb2 Nd5 12. exd4 b5 13. cxb6 Nxb6 14. Qb3 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 e4 16. Re1 Qd5 17. d3 Kf7 18. Qxd5+ cxd5 19. dxe4 bxa3 $11) 10... dxe3 11. Bxe3 (11. fxe3 $6 Nd5 12. d4 $2 b5 $19 {0-1 Cordova,E (2597)-So,W (2765) PRO League Stage Chess.com INT rapid 2019 (2)}) 11... axb4 12. Nbd2 Nd5 13. Ne4 Be7 $36) 9... axb4 $1 $146 10. O-O (10. dxe5 $6 Qg4 $1 11. Be2 Bxc5 12. O-O Ne7 13. exf6 gxf6 $15) 10... exd4 {the critical position. Here some important lines are:} 11. a3 (11. Re1+ Kd8 $1 12. Be6 (12. a3 Nc7 13. Qxb4 b5 14. Bxg8 Rxg8 15. Nxd4 Be7 16. Nc3 Re8 $13) 12... Nxc5 13. Qxa8 Nxe6 $13) 11... Bxc5 12. Qb3 b5 $3 13. Bxg8 Kf8 14. axb4 Bb6 15. Bc4 bxc4 16. Qxc4 Qe6 17. Na3 Kf7 $11) 9. b5 (9. O-O Na6 10. a3 axb4 11. axb4 Nc7 12. Qxa8 Nxa8 13. Rxa8 b5 $1 $15) 9... Nd5 10. exd4 Nf4 11. Kf1 $1 Qf5 12. d3 $1 Nxg2 13. Nbd2 {Cheparinov here checks 13...Nf4, but I can suggest to try} Qh3 14. Rg1 Ne3+ 15. Ke2 Nxc4 {and from here there are 2 critical lines:} 16. Rg3 {the best according to engine} (16. Nxc4 Bd7 $1 17. Nb6 cxb5 18. Qb3 a4 19. Qb2 Ra6 20. Nxd7 Nxd7 21. Qxb5 exd4 $13) 16... Qd7 17. dxc4 exd4 18. Kf1 $1 {Re1+ will come fast} (18. Ba3 h5 $13) 18... Be7 (18... Bxc5 $2 19. Ba3 $1 $14) 19. Rxg7 Qh3+ 20. Kg1 Bg4 21. Qc2 Kf8 22. Qe4 Kxg7 23. Qxe7+ Kg8 24. Qxf6 Nd7 25. Qg5+ Kf8 26. Qf4+ Bf5 $11 {and according to very strong engines the position is equal}) 7. b5 Bxc5 8. Bc4 {The only logical move.} Ne7 9. exd4 {has to be played.} (9. Ba3 $2 {Mistake.} Bxa3 10. Qxa3 c6 $17 {Black is much better here.}) 9... exd4 10. Ba3 $1 {The main line.} (10. O-O $2 {Famous mistake.} Bg4 $1 {And it is not easy to defend f3.} 11. Qb3 a4 12. Qd3 Bf5 13. Qe2 d3 {And the position is better for Black.} 14. Qe1 Qd6 15. Nc3 Qf4 $17) (10. Bb2 $2 {is also a mistake.} Bg4 $1 11. Nxd4 Qd6 $36 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Nd7-Nb6 next with huge initiative.}) 10... Bxa3 $1 {This is the strongest.} (10... Na6 {is the most played move, but the other move is stronger.} 11. O-O Nb4 12. Re1 Bg4 13. d3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Kf8 15. Nd2 Ned5 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Ng3 {White has some chances}) 11. Qxa3 {Psychologically harder to play because the knight on b1 is out of the game for now, but objectively stronger.} (11. Nxa3 $2 {It's a mistake.} Bg4 12. Nxd4 Qd6 $15 {And typical moves next.}) 11... c6 $1 {This is the cleanest equalizer.} (11... Bg4 {It can become quite tricky to play for Black after the normal line:} 12. O-O Nd7 13. Re1 Nb6 14. Bf1 Kf7 15. Nxd4 $13 {With some things yet to be understood.}) 12. Nxd4 cxb5 {And trade everything.} 13. Nxb5 Bxb5 14. Bxb5+ Nbc6 15. O-O O-O {And it is equal.} 16. Nc3 Nf5 $5 $11 {I wrote in my last file, but it is not the only move, many moves lead to equality.} 17. Bxc6 {White will most likely take.} bxc6 $11 {Equal material and few pieces left on the board.} *

