{[%evp 0,20,17,17,26,5,13,-13,-3,-12,-5,-17,-12,-11,0,-9,-8,10,5,4,-1,-6,-1]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 (2. b3 Bf5 {[%csl Yb3] It's very important to understand that we develop the bishop to f5 only after White has played b3—never earlier! If White's pawn is still on b2, he might have Qb3 ideas, creating problems on b7.} 3. Bb2 (3. Ba3 {without the inclusion of e3-Nf6, this is not so interesting for White:} Nd7 4. c4 (4. e3 $6 e5 5. Bxf8 Kxf8 $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gg8f6,Gh7h5,Gh8h6] strong center.}) 4... dxc4 $1 $146 5. bxc4 e5 6. Bxf8 Kxf8 $132 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gh7h5,Gh8h6] we can continue with Ngf6, and then slowly develop our h8 rook with h5-Rh6, especially if White castles kingside.}) 3... e6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Nh4 {it's always important to check this idea.} (5. Bg2 {mainline, and after} h6 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 Bh7 {we come to a position that will be analyzed in Chapter 6.}) 5... Be4 $1 {it's extremely important to provoke f2-f3.} ({but not} 5... Bg6 $6 {[%csl Gf2] because now White's pawn is on f2!} 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Bg2 Bd6 8. O-O e5 9. c4 c6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gf2,Gg2][%cal Gg2d5] Bg2 works very well.}) 6. f3 Bg6 7. Nxg6 (7. Bg2 Bh5 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gg7g5] now g5 is already a threat} 8. f4 {only move.} a5 $5 $15 {other moves like 8...Be7 or 8...c5 are also fine, of course.}) (7. e3 Bh5 $5 {White's kingside configuration is very anti-positional.} 8. Ng2 {[%cal Gg2f4] f4 next is the only logical continuation.} Bd6 $15 {Black is slightly better because Nf4 is bad.} 9. Nf4 $2 Bxf4 $1 10. exf4 (10. gxf4 O-O $17 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6] positional disaster for White.}) 10... d4 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6]}) 7... hxg6 8. Bg2 (8. e3 Bd6 9. f4 Qe7 10. d4 {Nakamura-Bachmann, 2024.} g5 $1 $15) 8... Bd6 {[%csl Rf3] With the pawn on f3, we have nothing to worry about.} 9. O-O e5 $15 {[%csl Rf3] compare this with the 5...Bg6 note. White's pawn on f2 or on f3 makes a huge difference.}) 2... Nf6 (2... Bf5 $6 {[%csl Gb2,Rf5] White's pawn is still on b2, so it's not a good moment for Bf5:} 3. c4 e6 4. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7,Rf5] this is why we play Bf5 only when White's pawn is already on b3, never earlier!}) 3. b3 (3. c4 {is White's main and most interesting move. It will be analyzed from Chapter 7 till Chapter 12.}) 3... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5] Once White plays b3, Bf5 becomes a very good option for us.} 4. Be2 $5 {more interesting than the natural 4.Bb2, and it has been played in the recent Ding-Gukesh, World Championship Match 2024.} (4. Bb2 {natural, but now Black will be in time to play e6+h6.} e6 (4... h6 {also possible, but I don't like} 5. Bxf6 $5 exf6 6. Be2 {Where the nature of the position changes drastically.}) 5. Be2 (5. Nh4 {this will be interesting for White in the 4.Be2 line, but not here because of} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Ge2,Rf1] this is why 4.Be2 is more useful than 4.Bb2!} 6. Be2 (6. f3 Bh5 {[%csl Rh4] problems with Nh4.} 7. g3 {[%cal Gh4g2,Gg2f4]} Rg8 $5 {not the only move, but I like to be creative here.} 8. Ng2 g5 $15 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gh5g6]}) 6... Bxe2 7. Qxe2 {[%csl Gc7]} c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next, and no problem, for example:} 8. O-O Nc6 9. f4 Bd6 10. Nf3 O-O 11. d3 (11. c4 d4 $1 $15) 11... d4 $1 $15) 5... h6 {[%csl Ge6,Gh6] Once Black plays e6 + h6 (useful against Nh4), all opening problems are solved.} 6. O-O (6. d3 $5 {could be tricky if Black is not accurate with the move orders.} Bd6 7. Nbd2 Nbd7 {we will castle only when White castles.} (7... O-O $6 {I wouldn't hurry with castle as White might have ideas like} 8. Rg1 $5 $36 {[%cal Gg2g4] g4 next.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Bh7 10. Bf1 e5 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Re8 $11) 6... Nbd7 7. c4 c6 8. Nc3 Bd6 $36 {[%csl Gf5] This is a Meran, with the bishop on f5. It's White who needs to think about equality.}) 4... h6 {my recommendation. It's more important to prevent Nh4 than Ba3.} (4... e6 {also possible, but it allows} 5. Nh4 $5 {which could easily become tricky for us.}) 5. Ba3 $5 {interesting extra option.} ({after the natural} 5. Bb2 {Black has zero problems} e6 {transposes in 4.Bb2, but Black is just fine.}) 5... Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ya3f8,Yd7f8] we prepare e6-Bxf8-Nxf8.} (5... e6 6. Bxf8 Kxf8 $132 {is also possible, but no need to play with the king on f8.}) 6. c4 ({or} 6. O-O e6 7. Bxf8 Nxf8 8. c4 {transposes in 6.c4.}) 6... e6 7. Bxf8 Nxf8 8. O-O ({don't be worried about} 8. cxd5 {[%csl Gf8] when our knight is still on f8:} exd5 9. Nc3 Ne6 $1 $36 {[%csl Ge6] Ne6 is very well placed. That's why White should think about cxd5 only once we play N8d7.}) ({or} 8. Nc3 c6 9. O-O N8d7 {transposes in 8.00.}) {Now, it's a very important moment.} 8... c6 $5 {My recommendation. The idea is to recapture with ...cxd5 if White plays cxd5.} ({After the natural} 8... N8d7 {White can play} 9. cxd5 $5 exd5 10. Nc3 O-O 11. b4 $14 {/= and the position is slightly more comfortable for White. This happened in the games Ding-Gukesh and Carlsen-Tari.}) 9. Nc3 (9. Qc1 $146 {engine's move, but it's empty:} N8d7 (9... Ng6 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] also possible, why not.}) 10. Qb2 O-O 11. d4 Qe7 12. Nbd2 a5 $11 {[%eval 10,0] is the engine's evaluation, but it obviously means nothing.}) 9... N8d7 10. cxd5 {is not dangerous now.} (10. d4 O-O 11. b4 {Andreikin-Bok, 2024.} (11. Qc1 Qe7 12. Qb2 a5 $11 {Eljanov-Gledura, 2023.}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 a5 13. a3 b5 $5 {good solution.} 14. Be2 Qe7 15. Qb3 Ra6 $132 {[%cal Gf8a8] Rfa8 next.}) 10... cxd5 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8] 0-0 next. I have played the Slav with Black—especially against the Exchange Slav—for my entire life. This is a position where White has zero ideas to create problems.} *

