{[%evp 0,28,26,26,19,-19,-15,-12,-13,-23,-25,-24,-12,-12,3,3,3,14,39,23,24,15,11,7,17,8,17,1,-11,-3,-10]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 e6 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 h6 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2 Bh7 {[%csl Gh7] Starting position of our Chapter, and it's a logical continuation of Chapter 5. I suggest to start with this useful-prophylactic move. The idea of Bh7 is that e2-e4 or Nf3-d4 (more rarely) will never come with tempo.} 9. c4 {White's most common continuation.} (9. Qe1 {[%cal Ge2e4] White's idea is clearly e4.} Nfd7 $1 {only one game, but it's the best. Next we want to continue with c5-Nc6.} (9... Nbd7 {natural move, but I don't like it because after} 10. e4 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5] White can continue with e5 later, and we will have to move our knight to the passive e8 square.}) 10. e4 c5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next, and it's slightly better for Black. Whenever White will play exd5-exd5, we will continue with Re8, and Qe1 will be misplaced.}) (9. Ne5 {harmless.} Nbd7 10. Nxd7 (10. Ndf3 c6 $132 {[%cal Re2e4] it will be very difficult for White to push e2-e4.}) ({or} 10. e4 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 c6 12. Qe2 Nd7 13. Bb2 Bf6 {transposes in 10.Nxd7.}) 10... Nxd7 11. e4 c6 12. Qe2 Bf6 $5 {I want to provoke e5.} 13. e5 (13. d4 {the best for the engine, but just for the equality.} b5 $5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] a5-a4 next.}) 13... Be7 14. f4 a5 $1 {we start a queenside counterplay.} 15. a4 (15. a3 $2 {looks logical but it's a mistake.} Qb6+ 16. Kh1 a4 $1 17. b4 c5 $17) 15... b5 $36 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb5a4,Yd7c5] bxa4 followed by Nc5 or Nb6.}) (9. Re1 {popular at high-level blitz games.} c6 10. e4 a5 11. a3 (11. a4 Na6 $36 {[%cal Ga6b4] our knight has the nice b4 square.}) 11... Qb6 {[%cal Gf8d8]} 12. Qe2 Rd8 $132 {[%cal Gb6a6,Gd5e4] we can continue with Qa6, followed by dxe4.}) (9. e4 {engine's first move, but it's also harmless:} dxe4 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. dxe4 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bb4 {[%csl Gb4,Re4][%cal Yf6e4] Nd2 cannot move because of the e4 pawn.} 13. c3 Bd6 14. Bd4 e5 15. Be3 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gd6c5,Ya7a5] Bc5 or a5 next.}) 9... a5 {[%csl Ga5] always useful move.} 10. a3 (10. a4 $2 {positional mistake.} Na6 $15 {[%cal Ga6b4] Nb4 next.}) 10... c6 {Famous position from the Reti / Reti-Slav. The position is playable, but White doesn’t have any dangerous ideas readily available. We should now examine how to react against the most popular continuations.} 11. Qc2 {the most common continuation.} (11. Bc3 {[%cal Gb3b4]} c5 $1 {as a rule, when White plays Bc3 it becomes a good moment for c6-c5.} ({even if you allow b4 by playing} 11... Nbd7 {the position will be equal:} 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Qc7 14. Qb3 e5 $11) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. d4 (13. e4 a4 $132) 13... Nc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Ge7,Gf6,Gh7] Black's pieces are much better placed.}) (11. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gd1a1] Useful move. Very often White's plan will be Rc2-Qa1.} Re8 {[%csl Ge8] Re8 more useful than Nbd7.} (11... Nbd7 12. cxd5 $5 {is an extra option for White.}) 12. Rc2 (12. cxd5 {now it's less good because after} cxd5 $15 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gb8c6] we can continue with Nc6 next. Bg2 is very bad.}) 12... Nbd7 (12... Nfd7 $5 {deserves attention.} 13. Qa1 Bf8 $132 {[%cal Gb8a6] Na6 next.}) 13. Qa1 c5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4] good moment for c5.} 14. cxd5 {if not cxd5, we will continue with d5-d4 with a good positional advantage.} exd5 15. a4 {only move, otherwise Black plays a5-a4, but now} (15. Ne5 $2 a4 $1 $17) 15... Nb8 $15 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] Na6-Nb4 next, and Black is preferable.}) (11. Ra2 {[%cal Gd1a1] very common continuation. White's idea is Qa1, and then slowly prepare b4 with Bc3-Rb1.} Qb6 $1 {very strong move.} ({after the standard continuation} 11... Nbd7 12. Qa1 Re8 13. Ne5 Bf8 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Bc3 $132 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gf1b1] the position is also equal, but easier to play for White.}) 12. Qa1 Rd8 {[%csl Gb8] useful move. For the moment we don't want to decide the position of our Nb8.} (12... Nbd7 {is also fine.}) 13. Bc3 Qa7 $1 $15 {[%cal Rb3b4,Gc6c5,Gb8c6] key move with the idea to prevent b3-b4. Maybe we will continue with c5-Nc6 next.}) 11... Re8 $5 {Analyzing these positions, I’ve noticed that Re8 is often more useful than Nbd7. This is because the knight on b8 has multiple paths: it could go to a6, or even to c6 if we manage to play c6-c5 at the right moment. In short, Nb8 can wait, and we will develop it in the most appropriate way depending on the position.} 12. Bc3 {[%cal Gb3b4] White prepares b4, which is the only sensible plan in my opinion.} (12. Ne5 Nfd7 $11) 12... c5 $1 {this is a very good move to play c5 with Nc6 next.} 13. cxd5 (13. e4 $2 {positional mistake happened in Bryakin-Svane, 2023.} d4 $1 14. Bb2 Nc6 $17 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gg8h8,Ge8g8] big positional advantage. We can continue with g5-Kh8-Rg8 next.}) 13... exd5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rd3d4] d4 is not possible because the queen is on c2.} 14. e4 Nc6 $11 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ga8d8,Yc6d4] very comfortable position for Black. We can continue with useful moves like Qc7-Rad8. Sometimes Nd4 is an interesting concrete option.} *

