{[%evp 0,6,29,20,20,13,13,13,13]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 {This is the starting position of the upcoming six chapters. It is essential to note that the lines in this position are intricate, with numerous possible move orders. Moreover, the theoretical part of this position has significantly evolved over the past 3-4 years, making it a new branch of the opening theory. To facilitate your study of these lines, I propose two distinct approaches. I recommend commencing with an in-depth analysis of the 15 model games. A thorough understanding of these games, including the associated move orders, strategic concepts, and potential improvements, should provide a solid preparation for the 2300/2400 level. For those seeking additional depth or requiring further study, an option is available to delve into the six theoretical chapters analyzed in chapters 7-12. This supplemental material is designed for players who wish to explore the intricacies of the position in greater detail. As you will notice, the 15 games I have selected are quite recent. Only one is from 2018, and two are from 2019, while the remaining 12 are from 2021 to 2024. This is because, as mentioned earlier, these lines are a part of a very recent theoretical branch} 4. Nc3 (4. b3 c5 {When White plays 4.b3, Black can go for the 4...c5 move} 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 (7. d4 $6 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb4+ $1 {Spoelmann-Fridman 2019}) (7. Be2 d4 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Bb5 {this concrete approach is analyzed in the game Harikrishna-Gumularz}) (7. Nc3 $5 d4 8. Na4 {Aronian-Pragg 2022}) 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 (9. Nc3 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Be2 {Ten-Kryvoruchko 2022}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc7 $1 {and here White has 3 main moves that are analyzed in 3 different games} 11. Nf3 {Santos-Dardha 2023} (11. Nc3 {Harikrishna-Bjerre 2023}) (11. Nd2 {MVL-Ding 2019})) 4... b6 5. b3 (5. cxd5 exd5 6. g3 {this is a very serious system played by Vincent Keymer in more than 20 games! It will be analyzed in the game Keymer-Ding 2023}) (5. d4 {White can transpose to the Colle system. The main ideas can be seen in the game Neiksans-Dreev 2021}) 5... Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. Rc1 (7. cxd5 exd5 8. d4 a6 9. g3 {this hybrid system is analyzed in the game Mendonca-Pragg 2021}) (7. g3 dxc4 $1 8. bxc4 e5 {Moroni-Brunello 2018}) (7. Be2 a6 8. Qc2 Bd6 {here White can try some g4 or Rg1-g4. This will be analyzed in the game Janzelj-Svane 2023}) 7... a6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne2 (9. Bd3 $5 {this interesting approach is analyzed in the game Dardha-Czpor 2023}) 9... c5 10. Ng3 (10. d4 $6 c4 $1 {Abelv-Motylev 2024}) 10... g6 {Malakhov-Anand 2021 I suggest taking a good time to study this introduction so that you will be able to understand the important games, the possible variations and the relative move orders} *

