{[%evp 0,50,24,24,27,9,19,19,19,-19,8,4,-4,-6,-6,-6,0,0,0,3,3,3,3,3,3,3,3,-10,-10,-10,-10,-10,5,-13,-10,-4,-7,-7,-7,-7,-7,0,0,-35,-7,-105,-69,-69,-41,-79,-32,-38,-39]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 {The main move, and just know that it is different from 3.b3, because there we develop the bishop on f5, but here we cannot, because White still has Qb3 ideas available.} e6 {A good move, and the only opening that involves d2-d4 we should study is the Colle, which is fairly a small opening, and one that doesn't pose problems (compared to the Catalan, Carlsbad, QGD etc).} 4. b3 {In Chapter 7 and 8, this move will be the focus.} c5 {I recommend this ambitious move.} 5. Bb2 {The main line.} (5. g3 {is a sideline.} Nc6 6. Bg2 e5 $5 {Good independent direction. There are not too many games here, only 11.} 7. cxd5 {The most natural move.} (7. O-O {Here, White is also risking.} e4 8. Ne1 Bg4 9. Qc2 $146 {Novelty, but very dangerous.} (9. f3 {We can just take it.} exf3 10. Nxf3 Be7 $15 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ge8g8] Good position for Black.}) 9... Nb4 {Good tempo move.} (9... Be7 {is also possbile, but that's another story.}) 10. Qb2 {Only good move, but this is a computer line.} Be2 11. Nc3 {White's idea.} Bxf1 {We can take the exchange.} 12. Kxf1 Be7 13. a3 Nc6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 {White will have compensation, but no advantage.} 15. Nxe4 O-O $44 {Very easy to lose this for White, over the board.}) (7. d3 {Engine says that is White's best, but it is pretty harmless.} dxc4 {We can go to an endgame.} 8. bxc4 e4 9. dxe4 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Nxe4 11. Ke2 Nd6 $36 {Black is not risking anything in the endgame.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Nc3 {Probably White should start with this move, but you can play any move.} (8. O-O e4 $1 {Strong move.} 9. Ne1 Qf6 {Good follow up, to attack the rook on a1.} 10. d4 {The best for the engine.} (10. Nc3 {is logical, but after} Nxc3 11. dxc3 Qg6 $17 {[%csl Re1,Ye4][%cal Gc8f5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] With the knight on e1, it is clear that Black is better.}) 10... Bf5 11. Bb2 h5 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gf6g6,Gh5h4] Easy play, better for Black.}) 8... Ndb4 9. O-O Be7 $146 {Already new position, the best line follows with:} 10. Ne1 Be6 11. f4 {White's idea.} exf4 12. Rxf4 O-O 13. Bb2 {Just slightly better for Black, any move is okay.} Rc8 $15) (5. cxd5 {is another try.} exd5 {But it is not a Tarrasch, because White has played b3 already.} 6. Bb5+ {Logical move.} (6. d4 Nc6 7. Be2 {It is not a good move order for White, as Black has now} cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 Bb4+ $1 {Important move, to disrupt the development.} 9. Bd2 Bd6 $15 {[%csl Gb2,Rd2][%cal Gc1b2] and White's pieces are badly placed.} (9... a5 {This move is possible, but needs to be understood.}) 10. Bc3 {You will always have the important tempo.} Ne4 $1 $15 {[%cal Rc3b2,Gd8h4] Bb2 back is not possible, because of Qh4.} (10... O-O $6 {was played in Hoffmann-Kuzubov.} 11. Nd2 $132 {I don't say it is advantage, but at least playable for White.})) (6. Bb2 Nc6 {transposes to the main line.}) 6... Nc6 7. Ne5 {Positionally critical, White wants to ruin the structure.} (7. O-O {is a natural line, but luckily Black has} Bd6 8. d4 cxd4 {And the bishop is worse on b5 than on b2.} 9. Nxd4 Qc7 {[%csl Rh2] With tempo.} 10. h3 a6 $11 {And White has to take on c6, but that is another strcture already.} 11. Be2 $6 {This is not the same.} Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Rd1d4,Rd6e5] And White cannot recapture with the queen.} 12. exd4 O-O $15 {[%cal Gc8f5,Re2d3,Gf6e4] And Black is slightly better, because of the better development.}) (7. Bb2 Bd6 {transposes to a line that we will discuss in Chapter 8.}) 7... Qc7 8. Bb2 Bd6 9. Nxc6 {The main.} (9. f4 $2 {is common, but it is a mistake.} O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 {The knight looks strong on e5, but in reality} 11. O-O Re8 $17 {[%cal Rd5d4,Gc8f5] It is just -1 position.}) 9... bxc6 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc8f5] is more precise, against Bf5.} (10. Be2 $6 {The normal square for the bishop, but Black can} Bf5 {develop the bishop to f5.} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 $15 {The structure is ruined, but fantastic two bishops. Slightly better for Black.}) 10... Qe7 {Simple move, to protect f6.} 11. Nc3 {Normal move.} (11. O-O $4 {Huge blunder.} Bxh2+ $1 {Typical tactic.} 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 h5 {Winning position.} 14. Kf3 Nxe3 $1 $19 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gc8g4]}) 11... O-O 12. O-O d4 {Other moves are also good.} (12... Bxh2+ $2 {Now it doesn't work, because the rook is on f8.} 13. Kxh2 Ng4+ 14. Kg3 h5 15. Rh1 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Rh5h4] And no h4 check.}) 13. Na4 Ng4 14. h3 Nh2 $36 {The best for White is Bxh7, but it has to be understood.} 15. Re1 $6 Qh4 $40 {With big attack.}) 5... Nc6 {Now White should take on d5, because if he doesn't, we will play d4.} 6. cxd5 {Natural.} (6. Be2 $2 d4 $17 {And we are very happy about this structure.}) (6. d4 $6 {is met with the typical idea.} cxd4 7. exd4 Bb4+ $1 {Annoying check.} 8. Nbd2 dxc4 9. Bxc4 {The best, but now White has the isolated pawn.} (9. bxc4 {would be nice, but} e5 $1 {And Black is better.} 10. d5 e4 $17 {Huge advantage.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gf6d5,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Just slightly better position.}) (6. g3 $2 {Same as 6.Be2.} d4 $1 {And fantastic structure.} 7. exd4 cxd4 8. Bg2 e5 $17 {Black is better.}) 6... exd5 {The starting position of Chapter 7 and 8, in this one we will check White's sidelines.} 7. Be2 {The second most played after 7.Bb5.} (7. d4 $6 {premature, because of the typical reaction} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb4+ $1 {[%csl Re1] Very important disturbing check.} 9. Bc3 (9. Nc3 $2 {is met with} Ne4 10. Rc1 Qf6 $17 {Big advantage.}) 9... a5 10. a3 (10. Be2 $2 Ne4 $1 $17) 10... Bc5 {This is the game Spoelman-Fridman.} 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O {With the bishop on c3, there is this important tempo} Ne4 {To hit c3.} 13. Bb2 Re8 $15 {Nice position for Black, slightly better simply.}) (7. Nc3 {Concrete line.} d4 8. Na4 Bd7 $1 {Very important move.} 9. Rc1 b6 {[%csl Yc6,Gd7][%cal Gd7c6] And thanks to the bishop on d7, the c6 knight is protected.} 10. exd4 {Critical, to win a pawn.} (10. Bb5 $146 {I mentioned this novelty also in 2024, still nobody played it.} Nb4 $1 {We are forced to enter a complicated line.} 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. O-O b5 {Otherwise, we could be positionally worse.} 13. exd4 {White sacrifices a piece.} bxa4 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxg7 {And White has some kind of compensation.} Rg8 16. Re1+ Be7 17. Be5 $1 {Only move, otherwise Black is much better.} Nxe5 {is another option.} (17... Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] is one option.}) 18. Nxe5 Kf8 $13 {It's a new position, unclear, but definitely it deserves to be tried by White, at least once.}) (10. Be2 {was played in Wei-Pragg, but most likely it will transpose, since White either way will have to capture on d4.} Bd6 {transposes to 10.cxd4.}) 10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Bxd4 Bd6 {We play for compensation.} 13. Be2 {Normal move.} (13. Qe2+ {This leads to maximum a draw for White.} Be6 14. Qb5+ Bd7 $11) 13... O-O 14. O-O {You can play for compensation in many ways.} Bxa4 {If you want a clear draw.} (14... Bf5 $44 {Full compensation.}) 15. Bxf6 {The best.} (15. bxa4 $2 {is of course met with} Bxh2+ $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d4]}) 15... Bxb3 16. Bxd8 Bxd1 17. Rfxd1 Rfxd8 $11 {Equal material, opposite color bishops, easy draw.}) (7. Bb5 {The main line will be discussed in Chapter 8.}) 7... d4 {Critical move, and it is my recommendation.} (7... Bd6 {possible but White can now play} 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {Where if Black plays Bb4+ then comparing to 7.d4 White is just a full tempo up as he has already played Be2}) 8. exd4 (8. Bb5 {is also a possible move.} Bd6 9. O-O {But I think this is a bit dubious.} (9. exd4 {will transpose to 8.exd4.}) (9. Na3 {was played in Nakamura-Niemann, 2024, but it is a pretty harmless move.} O-O 10. Bxc6 {It's the same.} (10. Nc4 Bg4 $15) 10... bxc6 11. Nc4 Bg4 $15 {Slightly better for Black position.}) 9... O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Bxd4 {The most logical, but now you have huge compensation after} (12. Nxd4 $6 {You are better with many good moves, Ng4 or Bg4, or just the simple} Re8 $19 {And it is probably winning, -1.50.}) 12... Bb7 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gc6c5,Gb7g2,Gd6h2] With idea of c5 and the bishops are very strong.} 13. Nc3 c5 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Re1 Qf6 $36 {Easy moves for Black, initiative.}) 8... cxd4 9. Bb5 {Only logical move.} (9. O-O $4 {is of course a huge mistake.} d3 $19) 9... Bc5 {Black is potentially better thanks to the d4 pawn, so White needs to play fast.} 10. Qe2+ {White's only idea.} (10. O-O $6 {too slow.} O-O $15 {[%csl Rb2,Gd4] Just positionally better.}) (10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qe2+ {will be the same as 10.Qe2+.}) 10... Be6 11. Qe5 {Critical.} (11. Bxc6+ {will lead to the same position.} bxc6 12. Qe5 Bd6 13. Qxd4 {transposes to 11.Qe5.}) 11... Bd6 12. Qxd4 O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. O-O {When we discussed this position in 2024, there were less games, now there are 6 new games, so almost the double.} Bd5 {[%csl Rf3] The best, to put pressure on f3.} (14... c5 {It is clear that this move is not the best for Black.} 15. Qc3 $146 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4] Still a novelty, and I am not sure that Black equalizes here.}) 15. Qh4 {It is clear that this is the way to play for White.} (15. Qd3 Be4 16. Qe3 Re8 17. Qg5 Be7 18. Qg3 Bd6 $11 {and White has nothing better than to repeat moves}) (15. Na3 {was played in Lu-Heinemann, but Black can clear cut equalize with} Bxf3 $146 16. gxf3 Bxa3 {The easiest.} (16... Qc7 $5 $13 {Or this is also possible, for a more complicated game.}) 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Bxa3 Rxd2 $11 {Equal endgame.}) ({the dangers of White's position could be seen after} 15. Ne5 $4 {that was played by my friend, Lucas Van Foreest in Kragero Open 2024.} Re8 16. Ng4 Nh5 $1 $19 {White resigned in a few moves, because too behind in development, Black was already winning, -4 position.}) 15... Bxf3 16. Bxf6 {Critical and now you have two options:} (16. gxf3 $6 {is met with the simple} Nd5 {And it's not compensation, but slightly better for Black.} 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 $15 {Just look at White's pawns.}) 16... gxf6 $1 {I think is much better, because we play for all three results, and it is easier to play with Black.} (16... Qxf6 {Black gets a slightly worse endgame, where it is possible to equalize, but we play only for 2 results.} 17. Qxf6 gxf6 18. gxf3 Be5 19. Nc3 {There was a recent game, Keymer-Shevchenko, but with good preparation, White can press a bit.} Rad8 20. Rad1 Rd3 21. Rfe1 Rfd8 22. Ne4 f5 (22... Rxf3 {Black took, but after} 23. Rc1 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 23. Ng3 Bxg3 24. fxg3 Rxf3 $11) 17. gxf3 Be5 18. Nc3 Qd3 $1 $132 {There are 2 new games here, Vidit-Vitiugov and Boyer-Poetsch, where Black scored 1.5/2, let's see what happened:} (18... Qxd2 $2 19. Ne4 $16) 19. Qh3 {was played in the game Vidit-Vitiugov, London 2024.} (19. Rfe1 $6 {was played by Boyer, but after} Kh8 $1 {It is already slightly worse for White.} 20. Re3 Rg8+ 21. Kh1 Qg6 {And Black played a nice idea.} 22. Qh3 Rg7 {To bring the other rook in the game.} 23. Rf1 Bxc3 24. Rxc3 $2 {was played in the game, but after} (24. dxc3 $1 {was the best, and for some reason this is equal, but very hard to understand.} Rag8 25. Ree1 {[%csl Rc1,Ge1] With the rook on c1 this is lost, with the rook on e1 it is equal.} Qg5 26. c4 $13 {Tough to understand.}) 24... Rag8 $19 {It is actually already lost position for White, you see very hard to play.} 25. Rcc1 Qg5 26. Rfe1 Rg6 {[%cal Gg6h6] And the game finished with a very nice mate in the end.} 27. Rcd1 Rh6 28. Qg4 Qd5 29. Qf4 Rxh2+ $1 $19 {[%cal Rf4h2,Gd5f3,Rh1h2,Gd5h5] White resigned since mate is unavoidable. Boyer-Poetsch, 0-1.}) 19... Kh8 {Black again played the typical plan.} 20. Kh1 Rg8 21. Rg1 $2 {White played the most logical move in the world, but after} f5 $3 {Suddenly Black is winning! Amazing position.} 22. Rae1 Qxd2 23. Nd1 {And here Black spoiled the advantage.} f4 $1 {[%csl Rd1] was the correct move, and it's game over. Domination!} (23... Bd4 $2 {was played, and the game later finished in a draw.}) 24. Qh5 Rxg1+ 25. Rxg1 Qd5 $19 {[%csl Rd1] The knight can never move, the queen can never move. Just -5 position.} *

