{[%evp 0,36,26,26,17,19,19,-14,-12,-15,-16,-10,1,-20,-4,-29,-10,-30,-12,-3,-3,-12,-3,-11,8,-2,4,7,16,2,22,-16,5,-23,0,-6,0,0,-8]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 {this is by far White's most common continuation.} Bd6 8. O-O (8. Nc3 O-O (8... Bg4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 9. d4 (9. Ne2 $6 {dubious idea.} Bd7 10. O-O (10. Ng3 a6 11. Be2 b5 12. O-O Qe7 $15) 10... a6 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Ne5 Bxe5 13. Bxe5 d4 $5 {we can fight for the initiative.} (13... Re8 $132 {is good enough for the equality.}) 14. exd4 Ng4 15. Bg3 cxd4 16. h3 Nh6 $15 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gh6f5] Nf5 next.}) 9... cxd4 {I think that this is even simpler.} (9... Bg4 {was my 2024 recommendation, and it's also very good:} 10. dxc5 Be5 $1 $146 {important novelty.} (10... Bxc5 $6 11. O-O {transposes to a theoretical position where White has chances for an opening advantage}) 11. Bxc6 {looks critical.} (11. Qd2 $6 Bxf3 12. gxf3 d4 13. Na4 Qd5 $15) (11. O-O Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxb2 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Ned2 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 a5 $13 {White has some compensation, but no more.}) 11... bxc6 12. Qd2 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nd7 14. f4 {the best, according to the engine.} (14. Na4 Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Re8 16. O-O-O Qh4 $44 {Black has a good compensation}) 14... Bf6 15. Ne2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Nxc5 17. O-O {this is equal after many moves:} Ne6 $11 (17... Re8 $11)) 10. Nxd4 Bg4 11. Be2 (11. Qd2 Nxd4 {the cleanest way for the equality.} (11... Bd7 $132 {also possible to have a fight.}) 12. Qxd4 Rc8 13. O-O a6 14. Bd3 Bc5 15. Qf4 Bd6 16. Qd4 (16. Qg5 {White can avoid the repetition, but it's also equal:} h6 17. Qh4 Be5 18. Na4 Bxb2 19. Nxb2 Qa5 $11) 16... Bc5 $11 {logical draw.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 (12. Bxg4 $2 {big mistake.} Nxg4 13. Qxd4 Qh4 $1 14. g3 Qh3 $17) 12... Bxe2 (12... h5 $5 {engine move, but maybe this is too much.}) 13. Nxe2 Qa5+ 14. Bc3 Qa6 $11 {[%csl Re2][%cal Re1g1,Ga6e2] very difficult for White to castle.}) (8. d4 {usually transposes to 8.0-0, but White has a sideline.} cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. O-O (10. Nd2 {rare but it was tried by MVL against Nihal.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {Black has many good continuations, the simplest is} Qa5 12. Be2 {only good move.} (12. Bd3 $6 {played by MVL, but it's a mistake because it allows} Bg4 $1 13. f3 Bh5 $1 {[%csl Re3] e3 is a weakness.} 14. O-O (14. Bxf6 $2 {looks critical but it's losing:} gxf6 15. O-O Bg6 $19 {[%csl Re3] e3 is too weak.}) 14... Nd7 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5] Nc5 or Ne5 next.}) 12... Bf5 {simple continuation.} (12... Ne4 {more concrete and is also possible.} 13. a3 Bxa3 (13... Nc3 $132) 14. Bb2 Nxd2 15. Rxa3 Nf3+ 16. Kf1 Nd2+ 17. Ke1 Nf3+ $11) 13. O-O Rfc8 14. Bxf6 Bc2 15. Qc1 Bf5 16. Qd1 Bc2 $11 {White is forced to accept the moves repetition.}) 10... Bc7 {transposes in 8.0-0.}) 8... O-O 9. d4 {the most common continuation. White wants to force us to play a position with the isolated pawn.} (9. Bxc6 $6 {very dubious plan.} bxc6 10. d3 Bg4 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Qc2 Nd7 $15 {0-1 Cebalo,M (2480)-Geller,E (2500) Bern 1987}) (9. h3 {useful move, but Black can use this tempo to develop the bishop on f5.} Bf5 {[%csl Gf5]} 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 (12. Qxd4 Bc7 $1 $36 {Qd6 next and h3 becomes a weakness}) 12... Ne4 13. Nc3 Qg5 $11 {equal for the engine, but OTB could be easier to play for Black.}) (9. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3a4] White could think about Na4 one day.} Bg4 {[%cal Ga8c8] natural and good.} (9... a6 {is also good according to the engine, but not everybody is ready to play the structure} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 $11) ({for example, if Black is slow and plays something like} 9... Re8 10. Rc1 h6 {White will be better after} 11. Na4 $16 {[%csl Rc5]}) 10. h3 Bh5 11. Be2 (11. Bxc6 $2 bxc6 12. Rc1 d4 $1 13. Ne2 Ne4 $17) 11... Bb8 $5 {maybe even stronger because White will no longer have the Nb5 tempo.} (11... Bc7 12. d4 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. Nb5 $1 {this is why 11...Bb8 might be slightly more precise.} (14. exd4 $6 Re8 $36) 14... dxe3 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nxc7 Qxc7 17. fxe3 $11 {but this is also equal after many moves.}) 12. d4 (12. Nh4 Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 $11 {[%cal Gd8d6] Qd6 next.}) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 cxd4 14. exd4 a6 $132 {[%csl Ga7,Rb2][%cal Gb8a7] Ba7 next.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc7 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8d6] White achieves an IQP position, but a good version for Black, who is ready to continue with Qd6 looking for some initiative on the kingside.} 11. Nf3 {the most logical move in my opinion.} (11. h3 {very slow. As a rule, after h3, Black's bishop can go to f5.} Re8 12. Nf3 Bf5 $132 {[%csl Ge8,Rh3][%cal Gd8d6] Qd6 next, and h3 can also be a weakness in the future.}) (11. Bxc6 {White's idea is to play against c6.} bxc6 12. Qc2 (12. Nxc6 $4 {huge mistake because of} Qd6 13. Ne5 Ng4 $19) (12. Ba3 Re8 13. Nd2 {was played by Sengupta in 2024. Black has many good moves, but a clear equalizer is:} Ng4 14. h3 {critical.} (14. N2f3 Qf6 15. Qc2 (15. h3 Ne5 $11) 15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Nf3 Qf6 18. Rac1 Bd7 $132 {[%csl Gc7,Gd7] more risky for White because we have two bishops.}) 14... Nh2 15. Re1 Bxh3 $1 16. gxh3 Qg5+ 17. Kh1 Qh6 18. Kg2 Qg5+ 19. Kh1 $11 {forced draw.}) 12... c5 $1 {clear equalizer.} (12... Qd6 {also possible if you want to play for the full point.} 13. g3 Bb6 $1 14. Qxc6 Qe5 $44 {[%cal Gc8h3,Ge5h5,Gh7h5] Black has full compensation thanks to the potential kingside initiative.}) 13. Qxc5 Ne4 14. Qc2 (14. Qc6 $4 {huge mistake, but it was played three times:} Rb8 15. Qc2 Bxh2+ 16. Kxh2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Rb6 $19 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb6h6]}) 14... Ba6 15. Rc1 Bxh2+ {forces a draw.} ({you can also decide to play on with} 15... Rc8 16. Nc3 Be5 $44 {Black has full compensation and a three-results position.}) 16. Kxh2 Bd3 $1 {important intermezzo.} 17. Qxd3 Qh4+ 18. Kg1 Qxf2+ 19. Kh2 Qg3+ $11 {everything ends with a repetition.}) (11. Nd2 {White's most common continuation, but here it's Black who plays for the initiative!} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Qd6 $1 13. g3 Ba5 {more precise move order.} ({is less precise to start with} 13... Bh3 14. Re1 Ba5 $5 {because now White can also play} 15. Bf1 $132) 14. a3 Bh3 15. Re1 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Ne4 {[%csl Rf3,Rg1,Rg2] White has two bishops but big problems on the light squares.} 17. Qb2 {[%csl Ya3][%cal Gb2a3] most logical move.} (17. Qe2 Rfc8 $36 {[%csl Ra3] always problems with a3 (no Rfc1 for example).}) 17... Qg6 {[%cal Ge4g5] preparing Ng5.} 18. f3 $1 $146 {the strongest according to the engine, but not too many players will be ready to go for it.} (18. Bd3 Bf5 $36) (18. Bf1 Bxf1 19. Rxf1 h5 $36 {very easy-to-play initiative.}) 18... Ng5 (18... Nxg3 {also fine if you want a draw.} 19. hxg3 Qxg3+ 20. Kh1 Qxf3+ 21. Kh2 Qh5 $1 22. Kg1 Qg4+ $11 {repetition.}) 19. Kf2 h5 $132 {[%csl Rf2] -0,05 for the engine, I am sure that everybody would prefer Black here.}) (11. Nc3 Qd6 12. g3 Bh3 13. Re1 Ba5 $1 {[%csl Rc3] most useful move.} (13... Rac8 14. Bf1 {playbable for White as happened in Harikrishna-Bjerre, 2023.}) 14. a3 (14. Bf1 Bg4 15. Be2 h5 $13) 14... Bxc3 (14... Ne5 $132 {also good.}) 15. Bxc3 Ne4 16. Bb2 Rac8 $132 {[%cal Gd6g6] Qg6 next. We are not better, but our position is easier to play.}) 11... Bg4 {Black's most common continuation and it's a direct and good move.} (11... Re8 $5 12. Nbd2 Qd6 {is an other possible direction}) 12. h3 {it's useful for White to include h3-Bh5.} (12. Be2 Re8 13. Nc3 (13. Nbd2 Qd6 $36) 13... a6 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Gb5d4,Rc3b5] not allowing Nb5-Nbd4.} 14. Rc1 Qd6 15. g3 Rad8 16. Na4 Ne4 $36) (12. Nbd2 {was the mainline in my 2024 file.} Ne4 {easy equalizer. Be careful because this move is not good when h3-Bh5 is included!} (12... Qe7 $5 {also possible if you want a fight.} 13. Rc1 Rac8 $132) 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Ne5 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Rd5 $11 {just draw as happened in Santos-Dardha, 2023.}) 12... Bh5 {most intuitive continuation.} (12... Bxf3 $5 {possible alternative. It's more ambitious but also more risky.} 13. Qxf3 Qd6 14. g3 Ne5 15. Qg2 {[%cal Gb2a3] White is ready for Ba3.} Ba5 {[%cal Ga5b4] we want to have Bb4 is case of Ba3. White has many moves, but the game goes for three results because White has a strange queen on g2, for example:} 16. Nc3 (16. Ba3 Bb4 $11) (16. a3 Rfd8 17. b4 Bb6 18. Rd1 (18. Nd2 Rac8 $5 $132 {[%csl Rg2]} (18... d4 $11)) 18... a5 $132) 16... a6 17. Be2 Rac8 18. Rac1 (18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Rad1 Rfd8 20. e4 Rc2 21. Rxd5 Rxb2 22. Rxd6 Rxd6 $13 {[%csl Rg2] very interesting position.}) 18... Bxc3 19. Bxc3 Qa3 20. Bxe5 Rxc1 21. Bxf6 Rxf1+ 22. Bxf1 gxf6 23. Qxd5 Qxa2 24. Qxb7 $11 {very likely it will be a draw.}) 13. Nbd2 Rc8 {Rc8 is the most useful move for Black, in my opinion.} ({be careful because now} 13... Ne4 $2 {[%csl Gh3,Rh5] is a big mistake with h3-Bh5 included because of the following variation:} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Nd4 c5 18. Nc6 Rd6 19. Ne7+ Kf8 20. Nf5 $18 {[%csl Gf5,Rh5] this move is possible now and it's winning.}) (13... Qd6 {Qd6 could be premature because White has the Rc1-Qc2-Qc5 idea:} 14. Rc1 Rfe8 15. Qc2 Rac8 16. Qc5 $14 {[%csl Gc5]}) 14. Rc1 $146 {novelty, but it's very logical.} (14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qc2 Bg6 $1 $15 {Vazquez-Plazuelo, 2021.}) 14... Qe7 (14... Be5 {I don't like it immediately because after} 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Rxc8 Qxc8 17. Be2 $14 {White has a risk-free pressure.}) 15. Be2 {[%cal Gf3d4] The most logical move. White is ready to play Nd4.} (15. a3 $6 {when a3 is played,} Be5 $1 {becomes good because sometimes a3 will be hanging:} 16. Bxe5 Nxe5 17. Be2 Nxf3+ 18. Nxf3 Qxa3 $15 {[%csl Ga3]}) (15. Bxc6 {concrete try, but harmless.} bxc6 16. Qc2 c5 17. Qf5 Bg6 18. Bxf6 Qd6 19. Qe5 gxf6 20. Qxd6 Bxd6 $11 {[%csl Gd6,Gg6] White has a better structure, but we have two bishops.}) 15... Rfe8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] prophylactic move against Nd4.} 16. Re1 {logical move to protect Be2.} (16. Nd4 $4 {huge blunder.} Qe5 17. g3 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Qxd4 $19 {[%csl Re2,Ge8]}) (16. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] normal continuation, with the idea to play b4.} a5 $132 {we can also prevent b4.}) 16... Bg6 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 a6 $132 {[%cal Ge7d6] Qd6 next and we are very fine.} *

