{[%evp 0,32,28,22,20,20,20,20,20,10,28,6,10,8,8,8,10,7,12,8,14,8,8,10,39,46,46,46,30,27,39,34,37,31,30]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 {My recommendation. 4...b6 keeps the game very independent compared to any opening against 1.d4 or 1.c4.} 5. b3 (5. cxd5 {will be analyzed in Chapter 11.}) (5. d4 {will be analyzed in Chapter 12.}) 5... Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 {Starting position of Chapters 9 and 10.} 7. cxd5 {Statistically, this is White's most played move, but for several years now, no strong player has used it—simply because it poses no real problems for Black. In fact, it is White who needs to be precise.} (7. Rc1 {Is White's most sensible line, and we will analyze it in Chapter 10. In this Chapter we will speak about White's less common options.}) (7. g3 {Now that White didn't include cxd5 exd5, Black can use this factor to his advantage by playing} dxc4 {not the only good move, but definitely the most interesting one.} 8. bxc4 e5 $1 9. Bg2 e4 {It's a position with only four games, but a very interesting one.} 10. Ng5 {The move that White played in all four games.} (10. Nh4 $146 Nc5 $1 ({not} 10... Ne5 $2 {because Black's knight on e5 will be hanging after} 11. O-O Qd7 12. Nxe4 $1 $16 {[%csl Re5]}) 11. O-O Qd7 12. d4 exd3 13. Bxb7 Nxb7 $13 {[%cal Ge8c8] 0-0-0 next. It's complicated, but I think Black's play is easier.}) (10. Nd4 $5 $146 {very interesting novelty.} Ne5 $1 {important move.} (10... Nc5 $6 {not good now.} 11. O-O Qd7 12. d3 $1 $14 {key idea and White is slightly better.}) 11. O-O Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] 0-0-0. If White doesn't find 12.Nd5, Black is just better.} 12. Nd5 $1 {only move and it is a very deep idea showed by the engine.} Nxd5 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Qh5 {[%csl Re5,Gh5][%cal Gh5e5,Gg2h3] White attacks Ne5 and prepares Bh3.} Bd6 15. Bh3 $44 {Full compensation for White, and it's equal after something like} Qd8 16. Nf5 g6 17. Nxd6+ cxd6 18. Qh6 Qf6 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Rfc1 Qd6 21. Qg7 Ke7 $11 {Equal, but still complicated.}) 10... Nc5 11. O-O h6 $1 {forcing White's knight into a passive square.} 12. Nh3 Bd6 13. d4 $1 $146 {the best for White, but just to equalize:} (13. f4 $6 Qe7 $15 {[%csl Rh3] Nh3 was very bad in Iturrizaga-Kollars, 2024.}) (13. Nb5 Nd3 14. Bc3 Be5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. d4 Nf3+ 17. Bxf3 exf3 18. d5 c6 19. dxc6 Bxc6 20. Nd6+ Kf8 21. Qd4 {Moroni-Brunello, 2018.} g5 $1 {keeping Nh3 our of the game} 22. Rad1 Rh7 $3 {threatening Qd7, where after Qxf6-Qxh3 White doesn't have Qxh8} 23. Kh1 Nd7 24. Nf5 Qc7 $19 {Re8-Qe5 next with a winning position for Black according to engine. It might look complicated but the key factor is that Nh3 is forever out of the game}) 13... exd3 14. Bxb7 Nxb7 15. Qxd3 O-O 16. Nb5 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gh3f4] Equal because White's Nh3 will go back into the game via f4.}) (7. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] Qc2 is very often misplaced.} c5 {My 2025 recommendation! Although this move is very rare, I believe it is the simplest way for Black. The main point is that Qc2 is misplaced.} (7... a6 {was my 2024 recommendation. It's a good direction, but now I believe that 7...c5 is much simpler.} 8. Be2 Bd6 9. cxd5 (9. g4 dxc4 10. g5 (10. bxc4 $2 Ne5 $17) 10... Ne5 $1 $146 (10... Ng4 $5) 11. Nxe5 (11. gxf6 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Bxf3 13. fxg7 Rg8 14. Qxh7 Rxg7 15. Qxg7 Bxh1 $15) 11... Bxh1 12. Nxc4 Nd7 $15 {Black is slightly better according to engine, but for sure, the position is still complicated}) (9. Rg1 h5 10. h3 h4 11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Kb1 dxc4 13. bxc4 b5 $1 $146 (13... Ba3 $6 {½-½ Janzelj,T (2443)-Svane,R (2647) AUT-chT 2324 Austria 2023 (6.3)} 14. Bxa3 Qxa3 15. Ka1 $14) 14. Ka1 (14. cxb5 $2 axb5 $19 {winning for Black according to engine}) 14... Nb6 15. Ng5 bxc4 16. f4 Ba3 $15) (9. O-O O-O {White can now play a sort of Colle system without d4. Black will continue with normal useful moves and will play c5 at some moment, whereas Whtie will have any way to play d4. The resulting positions are well-balanced and offer playable opportunities for both players} 10. Rac1 (10. Rad1 Qe7 11. Rfe1 c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. d4 Rac8 $11) 10... Re8 11. Rfd1 c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. d4 Rc8 $11) 9... exd5 10. Nd4 (10. Rg1 c5 11. g4 d4 12. exd4 O-O $15) (10. g4 $2 d4 $1 $17) 10... g6 11. O-O O-O 12. Nf3 $5 {White wants to be in time to play d4 in case Black will play c5} (12. Rac1 c5 13. Nf3 b5 $15) 12... Re8 (12... c5 13. d4 $11) (12... b5 $5) 13. Rac1 (13. d4 Qe7 $15) 13... Qe7 14. Rfe1 Rac8 15. Bf1 c5 16. d4 c4 $13) 8. cxd5 (8. Rg1 $2 {These plans, which were interesting against 7...a6, make no sense now.} g6 $17 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) 8... exd5 9. d4 {cxd5 followed by d4 is the only positionally sensible direction for White, but Black will have no problems due to—sorry for repeating myself—the misplaced position of Qc2.} Rc8 $1 10. Bd3 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Ne4 $11 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf8b4] and now you can see what I mean :).}) 7... exd5 8. d4 (8. Rc1 a6 {will be analyzed in Chapter 10.}) 8... a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] useful move against Nb5.} 9. g3 {White's only sensible deviation. The mix of b3 + d4 + g3 was considered interesting until 2022, but now it's clear that only Black can fight for something here.} ({of course, White can play the standard} 9. Bd3 {and after} Bd6 10. O-O O-O {it transposes to the Colle system, which will be analyzed in Chapter 12.}) 9... Bd6 10. Bg2 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] preparing 0-0-0.} 11. O-O O-O-O {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] And it turns out that Black's h5-h4 attack is much faster than anything White can achieve on the queenside or in the center.} 12. a4 $6 {White's most common and most ambitious continuation, but it's dubious.} (12. Qc2 {The strongest move according to the engine, but it's essentially an admission that White is now just trying to equalize.} h5 13. h4 {[%csl Gc2] Thanks to Qc2, White is more ready to face Ne4.} Rhe8 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4] Black better prepares for Ne4.} (13... Ne4 {not bad, but White is fine.} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Ng5 f5 16. Qc4 $13) 14. a4 Ne4 15. a5 (15. Nxe4 $2 {not good now.} dxe4 16. Ng5 f6 $19 {[%csl Ge8] this was the idea of 13...Rhe8.}) 15... Nxc3 16. Bxc3 b5 {easier to play for Black, but objectively equal.} 17. Ne5 $5 Kb8 (17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bxe5 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Rad1 $44 {[%cal Gd1d4] Rd4 next. Full compensation for White, but no more.} d4 $5 {just in case, this is a good equalizer.}) 18. Rac1 Nf6 $13 {Interesting fight, -0,20 is the engine's evaluation.}) 12... h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black's kingside attack is very quick.} 13. a5 (13. h4 Ne4 $17 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g5] f6-g5 next.}) (13. Qc1 Ne4 $1 {only move to get an advantage, but it's an easy one.} (13... h4 $2 {Harikrishna-Dominguez} 14. Nxh4 $16) 14. Nxe4 $2 {only move that has been played so far, but a huge mistake} (14. Qc2 Kb8 15. a5 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 b5 $17) 14... dxe4 15. Nd2 h4 $19 {happened in the game Mendonca-Praggnanandhaa, 2021. Black has a -3,00 advantage, according to the engine.}) 13... b5 $1 {important move.} 14. h4 Ne4 15. Qc2 Nxc3 $1 (15... Kb8 $2 {So-Dominguez} 16. Nxb5 $1 axb5 17. a6 $13) 16. Bxc3 Kb8 $17 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g5] f6-g5 next. Black has an easy attack, while it’s unclear how White intends to make progress.} *

