{[%evp 0,34,23,18,21,19,18,6,10,16,34,14,10,9,12,10,17,17,17,12,12,12,21,23,58,23,-14,-1,7,5,2,-19,1,-29,-31,-41,-32]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. Rc1 {White's most sensible continuation. We have already analyzed the sidelines in Chapter 9.} a6 8. cxd5 (8. g3 $146 {Nobody has ever tried it, but it's worth mentioning it.} dxc4 9. bxc4 Be7 ({not} 9... Ne5 $2 10. Nxe5 Bxh1 11. f3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Ge1f2,Gf2g1] Kf2-Kg1 next, and Bh1 is trapped.}) 10. Bg2 (10. d4 {[%cal Rd7e5] against Ne5.} c5 11. Bg2 b5 $1 $36 {Black has some initiative.}) 10... Ne5 $1 11. O-O Nd3 12. Rb1 O-O $15 {/= the position is between equal and slightly better for Black.}) 8... exd5 9. Ne2 {White's most common continuation.} (9. d4 Bd6 {transposes in the Colle, which will be analyzed in Chapter 12.}) (9. Be2 {not interesting for White:} Bd6 10. O-O O-O $132 {[%cal Gf8e8] Re8 next, and I don't see any good plan for White.}) (9. Bd3 $5 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3] More interesting than 9.Be2 because White will have the Ne2-Ng3 option.} Bd6 10. Ne2 (10. O-O O-O 11. Bf5 $5 $146 {Now, after g6, White will be able to play Bh3, where the bishop will control important squares like c8.} (11. Bb1 g6 12. d4 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Gf6e4] Ne4 next, and it's a typical position with no problems for Black.}) 11... g6 12. Bh3 Re8 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gb6b5] we can continue with Ne5, or with b5.} 13. Ne2 b5 $5 {the simplest way.} 14. d4 (14. Ned4 $6 {doesn't make sense.} c5 $17) 14... b4 $11 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Gb7a6] a5-Ba6 next (or just a5-a4).}) 10... c5 {[%cal Re2d4] against Ned4.} (10... O-O $6 11. Ned4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gd4f5]}) 11. Ng3 g6 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Rg3f5] only one game, but it's an interesting position.} 12. O-O O-O 13. a4 {[%cal Rb6b5] normal move that prevents b6-b5.} (13. Bb1 {[%cal Gd2d4] White plans d4, but we are slightly better after} b5 $1 14. d4 c4 $15) (13. Ng5 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4] The strongest, according to the engine. White's idea is f2-f4.} Be5 $1 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Bb1 d4 16. f4 Neg4 $13 {unclear ad open for all three results.}) 13... Qe7 14. Re1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Gd2d4] White prepares Bf1-d4.} (14. Bb1 {[%cal Gd2d4] White is ready for d4, but we can use the typical idea} b5 $1 15. axb5 axb5 $15 {and Black is fine because after} 16. d4 $2 {we have} c4 $19 {with a huge positional advantage.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Bf1 Rac8 16. d4 {[%cal Rc5c4] Now, Black cannot play c4.} Ne4 {typical good move. The position is just balanced and open for three-results, for example:} (16... h5 $5 {deserves attention.}) 17. Rc2 {useful move.} (17. Nxe4 {White wants to simplify the game.} dxe4 18. Nd2 cxd4 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. exd4 (20. Bxd4 $6 Bb4 $36 {Nc5 or Ne5 next}) 20... Nf6 21. d5 Bxd5 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. Nxe4 Bxe4 24. Rxe4 a5 $11 {full equality.}) 17... c4 $5 {now this is possible.} 18. Nxe4 (18. bxc4 $6 Bb4 $15 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rb2c3] no Bc3.}) 18... dxe4 19. Nd2 cxb3 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Qxb3 Bb4 {just equal:} 22. Rc1 Rxc1 ({but not} 22... Bxd2 $2 23. Rxc8+ Bxc8 24. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rd2][%cal Gc2c8,Gc2d2]}) 23. Bxc1 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Ga6a5] a5 next.}) 9... c5 {[%cal Re2d4] First of all, we prevent Ned4.} 10. g3 (10. d4 $6 {logical move, but Black has a strong resource:} c4 $1 {as was played by the strong GM Motylev.} 11. bxc4 dxc4 12. Rxc4 b5 13. Rc2 Be4 14. Rc1 Bb4+ 15. Nd2 O-O $36 {This is not just compensation, but initiative. Abel-Motylev, 2024.}) (10. Ng3 g6 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Rg3f5] useful move against Nf5. Now, it's important for Black to understand the different reactions against White's main tries 11.d4 and 11.Be2.} 11. Be2 (11. h4 $6 Bd6 $1 12. h5 Qe7 13. hxg6 fxg6 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8] 0-0-0 next.}) (11. Ne5 $6 {very harmless.} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Be2 h5 $15) (11. d4 h5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Gh5] remember: h5 is good against 11.d4 but not so good against 11.Be2.} ({after the natural} 11... Bg7 12. Bd3 O-O 13. O-O $14 {White has a better version of the 11.Be2 line because Bd3 is better placed, for example:} Rc8 14. Qe2 {[%csl Ra6] problems with the a6 pawn.}) 12. Bd3 (12. h4 Bd6 {[%csl Rd4,Ge2] and here we see, compared to the 11.Be2 line, that d4 is much less useful for White than Be2.} 13. Ng5 Qc7 $36 {[%csl Rg3]}) (12. Ne5 $2 h4 13. Ne2 {Vergara-Ostrovsky, 2024.} c4 $1 $146 {typical idea that we have already seen in the game Abel-Motylev.} 14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 b5 16. Nd2 Nb6 $17 {this is not only compensation, but it's a big advantage.}) 12... h4 13. Nf1 h3 $1 {useful inclusion.} 14. g3 Bg7 15. N1d2 Ne4 16. O-O O-O 17. Rc2 {Malakhov-Anand, 2021.} Qe7 $1 $15) 11... Bg7 {just normal development, and Black is fine.} (11... h5 $6 {not necessary now:} 12. h4 Bg7 (12... Bd6 13. Ng5 $14) 13. Ng5 $14) 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 {[%csl Re2] Be2 doesn't stay well.} Rc8 {we just want to improve the position with Qe7-Rfe8, and then push h5-h4, for example:} (13... Ne4 $6 {not immediately.} 14. Rc2 $14) 14. Rc2 Re8 15. Qa1 Qe7 16. Rfc1 h5 {[%csl Gh5] once we play Rac8-Qe7-Rfe8, we are ready for the h4-h5 plan.} 17. a4 {Mendonca - Radovanovic, 2022.} Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Nd2 Red8 $11) 10... Bd6 11. Bg2 (11. d4 c4 $1 $15 {similar idea to Abel-Motylev.}) 11... b5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Yd2d4] Thanks to b6-b5, we can be certain that as soon as White plays d2-d4, we will always be able to respond with c5-c4, which is our key idea.} ({if Black just plays normal moves like} 11... O-O 12. O-O Re8 $6 {White is slightly better after} 13. d4 $1 $14 {[%cal Rc5c4] because Black doesn't have the c5-c4 idea.}) 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 (13. a4 Re8 14. axb5 axb5 {[%cal Gb5b4] if we can push b5-b4, we will be slightly better.} 15. b4 $1 {good to equalize.} cxb4 16. d3 {White has full compensation for the equality, for example:} Nc5 17. Nfd4 Ra2 18. Rb1 Qd7 $11 {with a very balanced position. White has full compensation for the pawn, but no more than that as he doesn't have a clear plan to continue.}) 13... c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] our key idea.} 14. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg3g4] White plays for f4-g4, but we are faster on the queenside:} Qc7 (14... Rb8 $5 {deserves attention.}) 15. f4 Nb6 16. g4 b4 $146 {[%cal Gc4c3] preparing c3, and forcing White to act concretely.} 17. g5 Nfd7 18. bxc4 dxc4 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Rxc4 Nb6 22. Rc2 Rfc8 $36 {[%csl Ga6,Gb4] Black has strong compensation thanks to White's weaknesses on the light squares and the potentially dangerous 2 vs 1 majority on the queenside.} *

