{[%evp 0,42,19,29,23,12,10,-6,-6,12,25,28,21,-3,5,-13,33,33,8,-16,19,22,26,3,8,-5,20,9,17,17,1,-22,-13,-13,11,7,-3,12,32,21,15,14,27,11,12]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 5. cxd5 exd5 {White can play 6.d4 transposing to the Colle system or 6.b3 transposing to the 5.b3 line analyzed in Chapter 6. In this chapter, we will analyze the independent options} 6. b4 $5 {Nowadays, this is White's trendiest continuation. In 2024, there were only 8 games in this position, but now there are more than 20, with many games played by 2600+ players.} (6. Bb5+ c6 7. Be2 {this approach cannot be challenging from a theoretical point of view} Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 Bb7 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Rc1 Re8 12. Re1 {1-0 Dubov,D (2696)-Wei,Y (2734) CHN-ROW Summit Liaocheng rapid 2018 (1.3)} Ne5 $5 $11 {and Black has no problems}) (6. g3 {a serious move played more than 20 times by the strong and well-prepared GM Keymer Vincent} Bd6 {With White preparing to play Bg2, Black opts to postpone the development of Bb7, recognizing the potential opportunity to execute Ba6-Nc5 ideas in certain scenarios} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Yb8,Yc8,Ge8] waiting for White's next move} (8... Ba6 {it is also possible but better to wait until White has played b3 because} 9. Re1 Nbd7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nd2 {White didn't play b3, so Black now doesn't have Bb4 ideas as Nc3 is not so vulnerable. Still the position is around equal, but maybe White can hope for something small}) 9. Re1 $5 {useful prophylactic move against Ba6. This is the pet move of GM Keymer.} (9. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] Qc2 is misplaced and now we can play for c5-Nc6.} Bb7 $1 {[%csl Yd5] e defend d5 and are ready for c5-Nc6.} (9... Ba6 $6 {not a good idea here as White has Rd1} 10. Rd1 $1 $14 {Zwardon-Bartel 2022}) ({but not} 9... c5 $2 {immediately because of} 10. Ng5 $1 Bb7 11. Nxd5 $18) 10. b3 (10. Nb5 c5 11. Nxd6 Qxd6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6] White has two bishops, but we are ready for Nc6 next, and our pieces are great.}) 10... c5 11. d4 (11. Bb2 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Rc2] Qc2 is misplaced.}) 11... Nc6 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Rd1 Nb4 14. Qb1 d4 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 (16. Rxd4 Qe7 $36 {White is behind in development}) 16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Be5 18. Nc6 Qc7 19. Nxe5 Rxe5 20. a3 Qxc3 21. axb4 Qxb4 22. Bb2 Qb7+ 23. Kg1 Re6 $11) (9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] natural continuation because White wants to develop Bc1.} Ba6 10. Re1 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5d3] with the idea Nc5-Nd3.} 11. d3 (11. d4 {[%csl Rd4] against Nc5, but d4 is positionally bad.} Bb7 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga7a5] Ne4-a5 next, for example:} 12. Bb2 (12. Nd2 Ne4 $15) 12... Ne4 13. Rc1 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 a5 $5 $36 {[%cal Gd7f6] Nf6 next, and Black has the easier game.}) 11... Nc5 12. Bf1 {White takes control of the d3 square, but this approach is passive.} Ne6 {[%csl Ge6] very good square for our knight.} 13. Bb2 ({after} 13. Bg2 {we can repeat the moves with} Nc5 $11 ({or try to play on with} 13... c5 14. Ne2 (14. Bb2 $6 d4 $1 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Ne2 Bb4 17. Rf1 Nc5 $36) 14... Bb7 15. Bb2 Rc8 $132 {[%cal Gb6b5] maybe b5 next.})) 13... c5 (13... h6 {also good waiting move.}) 14. a4 Bb7 15. Bg2 a6 $132 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gh7h5] Rc8-h5 next.}) 9... Nbd7 {[%csl Gc8] our Bc8 is still flexible: maybe it will go to a6, or maybe on b7.} 10. d3 (10. b3 Nc5 11. d3 Ba6 12. Bf1 Ne6 {transposes in 9.b3.}) 10... Ba6 {my 2024 recommendation, it is also very good.} (10... a5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8a6] This might be simpler, with Ba6 next. For example:} 11. b3 (11. Nd4 {[%csl Rd4] Nd4 looks nice, but very often it is misplaced.} Bb7 $15 {[%cal Gd7e5] Ne5 next.}) (11. Re2 $5 Ba6 12. Rd2 {[%csl Yd3][%cal Gd2d3] engine's idea: now d3 is super protected, but it looks quite strange and we have an interesting game, for example after} Bb4 (12... b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4] concrete move, but you need to study} 13. Nd4 Ne5 14. Nxd5 (14. Ndxb5 {also possible, but after} Bf8 $44 {Black has full compensation.}) 14... Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bb4 $1 16. Bxa8 Qxa8 $44 {Full compensation.}) 13. a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd7c5] Rad8-Nc5 next. Easy play.}) 11... Ba6 12. Bb2 Nc5 13. Bf1 Ne6 $11 {[%csl Ge6] no problem for Black.}) 11. e4 {the strongest according to the engine.} (11. Nd4 $6 {Keymer-Pichot} Ne5 $1 $15) 11... Bb7 $1 $146 (11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bf4 Qd6 15. Qa4 $16 {½-½ Keymer,V (2696)-Ding,L (2811) Tata Steel-A 85th Wijk aan Zee 2023 (7)}) 12. Nh4 (12. Qc2 h6 $11 {[%cal Gd7e5] Ne5 next}) 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 Be5 14. Qc2 Nc5 15. Rd1 Qc8 16. f3 g6 $132 {very complicated position with equal chances}) 6... Be7 {Still my recommendation. I believe the most useful thing for us right now is to castle first, and only then decide how to react on the queenside against b4.} (6... Bxb4 $4 {is of course not possible because of} 7. Qa4+ $18) (6... a5 $2 {positional mistake.} 7. b5 $16 {[%csl Gb5] Fressinet-Lu, 2025.}) (6... c6 {looks solid, but after} 7. b5 c5 8. g3 $14 {[%csl Gb5] White is slightly better. This happened in Indjic-Kryvoruchko, 2024.}) (6... Bb7 {looks logical, but after} 7. Rb1 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb7] Bb7 could also be misplaced because it is now difficult for Black to play c7-c5.}) 7. Bb2 (7. Rb1 {This move was strong against 6...Bb7, but we have} Bf5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf5] big difference.} 8. Bb5+ {only interesting line for White.} c6 9. Nd4 {and now, we have a choice.} Bxb1 {concrete approach.} (9... Bd7 {positional approach.} 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 $132 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Ge7f8,Gc6c5] useful move that makes sure that we will have Bf8 at some point. c6-c5 will probably be our next move.} (11... c5 {I don't like it immediately because after} 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Nf5 $13 {[%cal Re7f8] we don't have Bf8.})) 10. Nxc6 Qd6 $1 11. Nxb8+ Kf8 12. Nc6 a6 13. Qa4 {Black is fine after many moves:} Bc2 $5 {leads to a complicated game.} (13... Bf5 {probably it ends in a draw:} 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. Nf5 Qe6 17. Nd4 Qd6 $11) 14. Qxc2 axb5 15. Nxb5 Rxa2 $1 16. Qxa2 Qxc6 17. Nc3 d4 $1 18. Ne2 dxe3 19. fxe3 Qxg2 20. Rf1 h5 $13) (7. b5 {logical positional move, but after} a6 $1 $15 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ra2a4,Ga6b5] no time for a4 because Ra1 is hanging.}) 7... a6 $1 {[%cal Rb4b5] preventing b4-b5, which is positionally very good for White. Important to notice that 8.a4 is not possible because of Bxb4.} (7... O-O {was played in Kaasen-Reuker, 2024, but after} 8. b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5]} a6 9. a4 $14 {White has a long-term positional edge.}) 8. Qa4+ $1 {only critical move.} ({Black feels well if White just continues the development:} 8. Be2 $6 O-O 9. a3 c5 $1 10. bxc5 bxc5 $36 {and Black is the one with the initiative.}) 8... c6 (8... Bd7 $6 9. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Rd7] Bd7 is misplaced.}) 9. b5 $1 $146 {the most critical move.} (9. d4 $2 {Eljanov-Schroeder, 2018.} b5 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Bf5-Nbd7-Nb6, and Black has a big positional advantage.}) (9. Bd3 b5 10. Qb3 Nbd7 $132 {[%csl Rb3,Rd3][%cal Gc6c5] c5 next.}) 9... c5 $1 {strong move which allows us to solve all the problems.} (9... Bb7 {is also fine.} 10. bxc6 Nxc6 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Ned4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 $36 {Objectively equal, but it's easier to play for White, in my opinion.}) 10. bxa6+ Bd7 11. Bb5 Rxa6 12. Qb3 (12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Nbxd7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf8a8] 00-Rfa8 next, and it's just an equal endgame.}) (12. Qf4 Ra5 13. a4 O-O $132 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next.}) 12... c4 $1 {my 2025 recommendation!} (12... Bxb5 {my 2024 recommendation. It's also good, but now I want to be even more precise.} 13. Qxb5+ Qd7 14. Ne5 Qxb5 15. Nxb5 O-O 16. Ke2 Rd8 $11 {It's an equal endgame, but maybe it's slightly more pleasant to play it from the White's side.}) 13. Qd1 (13. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] the queen is misplaced on c2.} Bxb5 14. Nxb5 Nc6 $132 {[%csl Rc2,Gc6] It's better for White to have the queen on d1. (for example, no d2-d3 now).}) 13... Bxb5 14. Nxb5 O-O {In this position, White's only idea is d2-d3.} 15. d3 Qd7 16. a4 (16. dxc4 dxc4 17. Qxd7 Nbxd7 18. Ke2 Ne4 $11 {equal endgame.}) 16... cxd3 17. Qxd3 Nc6 18. O-O {[%csl Ra4] we have an isolated pawn, but a4 is weak.} Ne4 $5 {might be even more precise.} (18... Rfa8 19. Nc3 Nd8 $5 $132 {[%cal Gd8e6,Ge6c5] Ne6 next, and then maybe Nc5.}) 19. Rfd1 (19. Nc3 Nb4 $1 20. Qd1 Bf6 $11 {no problems.}) 19... Nc5 $1 {allows a quick liquidation.} 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5 Rxa4 $11 {Just equal endgame. We can say that the only real danger against 6.b4 is ending up in a slightly unpleasant position, but if we play precisely, White has nothing—in fact, he also needs to be accurate!} *

