{[%evp 0,40,26,26,16,10,12,-4,6,21,31,24,28,9,33,9,22,12,39,23,16,2,10,4,10,8,0,-9,-15,0,-8,-27,-5,-37,4,-28,21,0,4,0,0,2,5]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 5. d4 {[%csl Gb6] In the final Chapter 12, we will explore the Colle System in a version where Black has already committed to b7-b6—which, as we will see, is not a bad move.} Bd6 {[%csl Gc8] Remember this move order: We shouldn’t rush with Bb7.} ({After the natural} 5... Bb7 {White has some extra ideas, for example:} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qa4+ $5 (7. Bb5+ $5 c6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. e4 $1 $14) 7... c6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. e4 $1 $14) 6. Bd3 (6. cxd5 exd5 {the extra ideas 7.Qa4+ and 7.Bb5+ are not so interesting against the 5...Bd6 move order.} 7. Bb5+ $6 {this was interesting against the 5...Bb7 move order, but not here.} (7. Qa4+ $6 c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 $36 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Re3e4] White doesn't have e4, and Qa4 is just misplaced.}) 7... c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Qe7 {[%cal Re3e4] no e4.} 10. Qc2 Re8 11. b3 (11. Re1 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5] probably we will develop our bishop on f5, not on b7.}) 11... Ne4 12. Bb2 Nd7 13. Rac1 Bb7 $15) 6... O-O 7. O-O Bb7 {we can consider this as the starting position of our Colle.} 8. b3 (8. Qe2 {not so interesting for White because now we have} c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] and no problem, for example:} 9. Rd1 (9. dxc5 bxc5 10. Rd1 (10. e4 $6 d4 $15) 10... Qb6 $132 {[%csl Gb8] we can still decide where to develop our Nb8.}) 9... dxc4 {the simplest.} (9... Nc6 {also good.}) 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. e4 {critical, but it's White who will need to equalize after} (11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. a3 Qb8 $5 $11) 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qb8 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] our plan is a6-b5.} 13. f4 $1 $146 {only move for White to equalize.} (13. g3 $6 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb6b5] b5 next, and Black is preferable.}) 13... Bxf4 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Nxe6 $1 {key idea.} fxe6 16. Bxe6+ Kh8 17. Bxd7 $11 {equal after many moves.}) (8. cxd5 {White's second most common move.} exd5 9. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] Most common move, but Qc2 is misplaced.} (9. b3 {is White's best continuation, but after} a6 10. Bb2 Nbd7 {it will be analyzed via the 8.b3 move order.}) (9. Nb5 Be7 10. Qc2 c5 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb8c6] Qc2 is misplaced. Just Nc6 next.} 11. b3 Nc6 $11) 9... c5 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next. This is a typical idea against White's queen on c2.} 10. b3 (10. Nb5 $6 c4 $1 $15) (10. dxc5 bxc5 $36) 10... Nc6 11. dxc5 $6 {was tried in Harikrishna-Mendonca, 2024.} (11. a3 Re8 $132 {very comfortable for Black.}) 11... bxc5 12. Bb2 d4 $1 $17 {Black is already better.}) 8... Re8 {[%csl Ge8] more useful than Nbd7.} (8... Nbd7 {looks normal, but White has the interesting extra option} 9. cxd5 $5 exd5 10. Nb5 Be7 11. Ba3 $5 {which could lead to a sligthly more comfortable game for White.}) 9. Bb2 (9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nb5 Bf8 11. Ba3 {this extra option is not so good now with the knight on b8:} Bxa3 12. Nxa3 c5 $1 $11 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb8c6,Gf6e4,Ga3b5,Gb5c3] Nc6 next.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Rc1 {has to be played at some point.} a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] we kill all White's Nb5 ideas.} 11. cxd5 (11. Na4 $6 {White's second most common move. It's dubious but concrete.} dxc4 12. bxc4 e5 $1 {important move.} 13. c5 (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 $15 {comfortable and slightly better for Black.}) 13... e4 $1 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Be2 exf3 16. Bxf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 b5 18. Nc3 Nb6 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb6c4,Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga8c8,Gc8c4]}) (11. Ne2 $6 dxc4 $1 12. Bxc4 (12. bxc4 c5 $15) 12... b5 13. Bd3 c5 $36 {Grebnev-Svane, 2024.}) 11... exd5 12. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3] Ne2-Ng3 standard plan for White, the only sensible plan I would say.} (12. Qc2 Ne4 $1 13. Ne2 Rc8 14. Ng3 g6 15. Qe2 {transposes in 12.Ne2.}) (12. Re1 {doesn't make sense because of} Ne4 $132 {[%csl Re1,Ge4] Ne4 more useful than Re1.}) 12... Ne4 13. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5]} g6 {[%cal Rg3f5] useful move against Nf5.} 14. Qc2 {and this is an important moment.} (14. Rc2 {harmless.} Qe7 15. Qe2 h5 16. Rfc1 c6 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4,Ga6a5,Gf7f5]}) 14... Rc8 {[%csl Gc7] important move to protect c7.} (14... Qe7 {looks natural, but now White has} 15. Ne5 $1 {and the game becomes more unclear. The main idea is that after} Nxe5 $2 {[%csl Rc7] we will have problems with c7:} 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Qxc7 Qxc7 20. Rxc7 $16 {very unpleasant endgame.}) 15. Qe2 (15. Rfd1 Ndf6 $36 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf6g4] Ng4 next and if White plays Ne5, then Nxg3-hxg3-c5 is a strong reaction.}) 15... a5 $5 {I don't want to go for the 15...Ra8 moves repetition.} (15... Ra8 {many games finished with a repetition after Ra8-Qc2-Rc8-Qe2.} 16. Rc2 $5 {extra option for White.}) 16. Rc2 {[%cal Gf1c1] White's only improvement is Rc2-Rfc1.} h5 {[%csl Gh5] useful move.} 17. Rfc1 c6 {[%csl Gc6] with a complex game. White might try putting extra pressure on the c6 pawn with} 18. Ba6 {but after} Bxa6 19. Qxa6 Bxg3 20. hxg3 Re6 $11 {[%csl Gc6] The c6 weakness is not easy to exploit, and Black has some potential initiative on the kingside. This was the last chapter of 1.Nf3 d5 for Black Part 1, 2025 version, but you still have many instructive model games with video lessons, and I highly recommend checking them out. Good luck, and see you soon for 1.Nf3 d5 for Black Part 2, where we will examine the main 2.g3 variation!} *

