1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 5. d4 Bd6 $1 {A more favorable move order, given that the lines involving cxd5, exd5, Qa4+, and Bb5+ tend to result in less favorable positions for White in this situation} ({For example} 5... Bb7 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qa4+ $5 c6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. e4 $1 $14) 6. Bd3 (6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qa4+ $6 c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 $36 {Where Black has no problems and the more pleasant game}) 6... O-O 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 (8. Qe2 c5 $1 {and Black has a good game}) (8. cxd5 exd5 {At this point, White has the option to play 9.b3, transposing into the main line. Other alternatives seem less threatening, where Black might even fight for the initiative} 9. Qc2 c5 $1) 8... Re8 (8... Nbd7 9. cxd5 $5 exd5 10. Nb5 Be7 11. Ba3 {could be interesting for White}) 9. Bb2 (9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nb5 Bf8 11. Ba3 Bxa3 12. Nxa3 c5 $1 $11 {Nc6 next}) 9... Nbd7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 a6 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Ng3 g6 14. Qc2 (14. Rc2 Qe7 15. Qe2 h5 16. Rfc1 c6 $132) 14... Rc8 {many games now are finishing with the repetition Qe2-Ra8-Qc2-Rc8} 15. Qe2 Ra8 16. Qc2 Rc8 17. Qe2 (17. Rfd1 Ndf6 $36 {Ng4 next and if White plays Ne5, then Nxg3-hxg3-c5 is a strong reaction}) 17... Ra8 (17... a5 $5 {Black can also decide to play on with} 18. Rc2 h5 19. Rfc1 c6 {with a complex game. White might try to put extra pressure over the c6 pawn with} 20. Ba6 {but after} Bxa6 21. Qxa6 Bxg3 22. hxg3 Re6 $11 {the c6 weakness is not easy to exploit and Black has some potential initiative on the kingside}) 18. Qc2 1/2-1/2

